= \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Hato Abajo''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[Arecibo, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 19,699.<ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhen after the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)]], the U.S. conducted its first census of Puerto Rico, the population of Hato Abajo barrio was 1,869.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n251 160]| language=es}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of Arecibo, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "reworded history paragraph, replaced: When after \u2192 The United", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hato_Abajo,_Arecibo,_Puerto_Rico"}
{"title_page": "Urawa Red Diamonds", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Urawa Red Diamonds Ladies}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = {{nihongo|Reds|\u30ec\u30c3\u30ba|Rezzu}} / {{nihongo|Red Devils|\u8d64\u3044\u60aa\u9b54|Akai Akuma}}\n| ground   = [[Saitama Stadium 2002]]<br>[[Midori-ku, Saitama|Midori-ku]], [[Saitama (city)|Saitama]]\n| capacity = 63,700\n| pattern_la1 = _urawa20h\n| pattern_b1  = _urawa20h\n| pattern_ra1 = _urawa20h\n| pattern_sh1 = _Urawa Red Diamonds 2009 HOME FP\n| pattern_so1 = _nikefootballwhitelogo\n| leftarm1    = FF0000\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FF0000\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = 000000\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _urawa_reds_2020a\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _nikefootballredlogo\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = E90000\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la3= _urawa20t                    \n| pattern_b3= _urawa20t            \n| pattern_ra3= _urawa20t                    \n| pattern_sh3=                     \n| pattern_so3= _nikefootballblacklogo\n| leftarm3=                        \n| body3=   \n| rightarm3=         \n| shorts3= 000                        \n| socks3= E90000\n| clubname = Urawa Reds\n| image    = [[Image:UrawaReds.png|211px|Club crest]]\n| fullname = Urawa Red Diamonds\n| founded  = {{Start date and age|1950}}\n| owner    = [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]]\n| chairman = Keizo Fuchita\n| manager = [[Tsuyoshi Otsuki]]\n| league   = [[J1 League]]\n| season   = [[2019 J1 League|2019]]\n| position = J1 League, 14th of 18\n| current  = 2020 Urawa Red Diamonds season\n| website  = http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp\n}}\n\n[[Image:MitsubishiUrawaFC.png|logo|thumb|130px|Old crest]]\n{{nihongo|'''Urawa Red Diamonds'''|\u6d66\u548c\u30ec\u30c3\u30c9\u30c0\u30a4\u30e4\u30e2\u30f3\u30ba|Urawa Reddo Daiyamonzu}}, colloquially '''Urawa Reds''' (\u6d66\u548c\u30ec\u30c3\u30ba), are a Japanese professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Saitama (city)|Saitama]], part of the [[Greater Tokyo Area]]. The club plays in the [[J1 League]], which is the top tier of football in the country.  Its name comes from the former city of [[Urawa, Saitama|Urawa]], which is now a part of Saitama City.\n\nThe name Red Diamonds alludes to the club's pre-professional era parent company [[Mitsubishi]]. The corporation's logo consists of three red diamonds, one of which remains within the current club badge.\n\n==History==\nShin-Mitsubishi Heavy Industries established a football club in 1950<ref>[http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/Club/mitu.htm \u6d66\u548c\u30ec\u30c3\u30ba\u5e74\u8868] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025012457/http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/Club/mitu.htm |date=2008-10-25 }}, Urawa Red Diamonds</ref> in [[Kobe]] and moved the club to Tokyo in 1958. In [[1965 in Japanese football|1965]] it formed the [[Japan Soccer League]] along with today's [[Sanfrecce Hiroshima]], [[JEF United Ichihara Chiba]], [[Kashiwa Reysol]], [[Cerezo Osaka]] and three other clubs who have since been relegated to regional leagues.\n\nMitsubishi first won the JSL championship in 1969, as a break in Mazda/Sanfrecce's dominance (and also with the fact that Toyo were in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], competing in the [[1969 Asian Club Championship|Asian Club Cup]]); their runs up the first division were sporadic but steady until the 1980s when they fell into the Second Division. In 1990 they were promoted as JSL 2 champions, and thus were ready when the J-League implementation began in earnest.\n\nMitsubishi were the first Japanese club to complete a domestic [[The Treble|treble]], when in 1978 they won the title, the [[Emperor's Cup]] and the [[Japan Soccer League Cup]].\n\nThe club has enjoyed mixed fortunes since the J-League advent. The club finished bottom of the league for the first two seasons of the J-League with an average crowd of under 15,000. In 1999 they suffered relegation to the second tier of Japanese football yet again. The team has since improved in form in recent years, starting with a 2003 victory in the [[J.League Cup|Nabisco Cup]].\n\nIn [[2006 J.League Division 1|2006]] Urawa clinched their first professional league title by defeating runners-up [[Gamba Osaka]] 3\u20132 on December 2 before 63,000 supporters. This came after two close calls in the previous two years.  In [[2005 J.League Division 1|2005]], they finished 2nd, one point behind champions [[Gamba Osaka]]. In [[2004 J.League Division 1|2004]], they finished 3rd in the first stage and won the second stage. Having qualified for the two-match [[J.League Championship]] decider, they lost on penalty kicks to [[Yokohama F. Marinos]].\n\nUrawa were back to back [[Emperor's Cup]] winners in 2005 and 2006. Winning the title for the first time since establishment as a professional team, they defeated [[Shimizu S-Pulse]] 2\u20131 on January 1, 2006, and retained the title in 2007 with a 1\u20130 win over Gamba Osaka. This win also completed a [[Double (association football)|league-cup double]]. In the 2007 tournament they were defeated at the first hurdle by J2 outfit [[Ehime FC]].\n\nIn 2007, despite a seemingly unassailable lead of seven points with four games remaining, Urawa picked up only two points from their final four games. This run included losing at home to Kashima Antlers; the team who would leapfrog Urawa on the final day of the season to claim their fifth J.League title. Following their capitulation in the fourth round of the Emperor's Cup to J2 outfit [[Ehime FC]], Urawa had to be content with their [[2007 AFC Champions League|2007]] Asian Champions League title. Urawa recorded their first international title after overcoming [[Iran]]ian team [[Sepahan F.C.]] 3\u20131 on aggregate. The victory made them the first Japanese side to win the title since the competition was reorganised from the Asian Champions Cup in 2003. In the [[FIFA Club World Cup 2007|Club World Cup]] of the same year, Urawa became the first [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] team to finish in third place, beating Tunisian [[\u00c9toile Sportive du Sahel]] side on penalty kicks in the third / fourth place play off.\n\nIn 2008, Urawa attempted to win their second consecutive Asian Champions League title and progressed to the semi finals where they were defeated by fellow J-League rivals, and eventual Champions League winners, Gamba Osaka 3\u20131 on aggregate.\n\nOn March 8, 2014, a banner which read \"JAPANESE ONLY\" was hung at one of the entrances to the stands.<ref>{{cite web|last1=ARUDOU|first1=DEBITO|title=J.League and media must show red card to racism|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2014/03/12/issues/j-league-and-media-must-show-red-card-to-racism#.VuQK6OJ9600|website=Japan Times|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> As punishment for this racist behavior, the March 23 match was played in an [[Behind closed doors (sport)|empty stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Urawa Reds play to empty stadium after fans banned for racist banner|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/26704368|website=BBC|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International affiliation==\nThe club is also notable in that former [[Feyenoord Rotterdam|Feyenoord]] midfielder [[Shinji Ono]] began his professional career playing for Urawa. Ono returned for the 2006 season for a second stint with the club. Urawa is affiliated with German club [[FC Bayern Munich]], whose nickname is also \"The Reds\".<ref>[http://www.fcbayern.t-com.de/en/news/news/2006/10290.php?fcb_sid=35f5052063f6b7de9b0396ef5439f39d\u3000J-League partner Urawa seal domestic double], FC Bayern</ref> [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]], the chairman of the FC Bayern Munich, announced that \"We have been looking for clubs which have potential ability, management stability and cordial confidence. We could fulfill the desire to affiliate with this great club, Urawa Reds.\"<ref>[http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/Club/fcb05-06.htm 06.01.18 FC\u30d0\u30a4\u30a8\u30eb\u30f3\u30fb\u30df\u30e5\u30f3\u30d8\u30f3(\u30c9\u30a4\u30c4)\u3068\u306e\u30d1\u30fc\u30c8\u30ca\u30fc\u30b7\u30c3\u30d7\u7de0\u7d50\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208081052/http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/Club/fcb05-06.htm |date=2008-12-08 }}, Urawa Red Diamonds</ref> Some other foreign clubs, such as [[Arsenal F.C.]], [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente]], [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo]], [[VfB Stuttgart]], [[Manchester United F.C.]], [[Feyenoord]], [[Hamburger SV]] and [[Perth Glory FC]], visited Japan and played friendly games at the Saitama Stadium.\n\nIn August [[2004 in association football|2004]], Urawa appeared in a pre-season four-team friendly tournament, the Vodafone Cup, at [[Old Trafford]], the home of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].  The Japanese club, missing key players, lost their first game 5\u20132 against the Argentinian side [[Boca Juniors]].  The second fixture against the hosts, Manchester United, was called off due to a massive electric storm.  Some 800 Urawa fans had travelled to the game and were later compensated.\n\nThe club's supporters also have an unofficial relationship with [[Shanghai Shenhua]]. The clubs' supporters will support each other in continental competition. For example, Shenhua fans will support Urawa when Urawa plays in Shanghai against Shanghai SIPG.<ref>[https://wildeastfootball.net/2017/03/urawa-shenhua-alliance-shows-football-has-no-borders/]</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Manchester united vs urawa red diamonds.jpg|thumb|right|International friendly match against Manchester United, July 30, 2005, [[Saitama Stadium]]]]\nSince the establishment of J.League in 1992, the team had used tracked [[Urawa Komaba Stadium]] as its home stadium. Due to the increasing popularity of the matches, Saitama City, owner of the stadium, expanded the seat capacity some times. The team used [[\u014cmiya Park Soccer Stadium]] until the works were complete. In spite of the poor performance of the team, the stadium was filled with faithful supporters, drawing an average audience of twenty thousand people.\n\nIn October 2001, [[Saitama Prefecture]] built new football-specific [[Saitama Stadium]] in Saitama city. This stadium was used as a venue for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. After the World Cup the club gradually increased home games in Saitama Stadium and in 2003 the stadium was formally designated as the home stadium. In 2008, only two games were held at Komaba Stadium.\n\n==Facilities==\nUrawa Reds uses Ohara City Field for training. In addition to this facility, the club opened Redsland in 2005, which has three grass fields, one [[artificial turf]] field, one [[baseball]] field, [[futsal]] courts and [[tennis courts]].<ref>[http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/redsland/index.html \u30ec\u30c3\u30ba\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9 | \u6d66\u548c\u30ec\u30c3\u30ba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024211422/http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/redsland/index.html |date=2008-10-24 }}, Urawa Red Diamonds</ref> Redsland is opened to the public and club members can use the facilities at relatively cheap fees.\n\n==Rivalries==\nUrawa Red Diamonds has a [[local derby]] with [[Omiya Ardija]], from [[\u014cmiya-ku, Saitama]] city. They first met in the [[1987 Emperor's Cup]], with Mitsubishi defeating NTT Kanto by 5 to 0 at [[Nishigaoka National Stadium]]. The derby first took place in the JSL Second Division in the [[1989\u201390 Japan Soccer League|1989\u201390 season]], and it wouldn't take place until the [[2000 J.League Division 1|2000 season]] when Urawa was relegated to the second tier again. In 2003 the formerly separate Omiya and Urawa cities merged to become [[Saitama, Saitama|Saitama city]], and since 2005 the derby became a top flight fixture after Omiya was promoted.\n\nDuring the JSL years and into the 1990s, Urawa's main top flight rivals were [[JEF United Ichihara Chiba]] and [[Kashiwa Reysol]], both now based in [[Chiba Prefecture]]. Because of their former parent companies' headquarters being all based in [[Marunouchi]], Tokyo, the three clubs were known as \u4e38\u306e\u5185\u5fa1\u4e09\u5bb6 ''Marunouchi Gosanke'' (\"Marunouchi Big Three\") and fixtures between them were known as ''Marunouchi derbies'', although the term is falling out of use as they are now based in different prefectures and rarely play home games in Tokyo stadiums.\n\nRivals further afield include [[Kashima Antlers]], [[FC Tokyo]], [[Yokohama Marinos]], [[Kawasaki Frontale]], and, even farther away, [[Gamba Osaka]]. Old JSL championship rivalries with [[Sanfrecce Hiroshima]], [[Cerezo Osaka]] and [[Shonan Bellmare]] have ebbed down as those clubs had nadirs in the second tier.\n\n==Women's and Amateur Teams==\nThe club also has [[Women's association football|women's]] and amateur teams.\n* Women's: [[Urawa Red Diamonds Ladies]]<ref>[http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/ladies/index.html URAWA REDS LADIES] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024212240/http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/ladies/index.html |date=2008-10-24 }}, Urawa Red Diamonds</ref>  in [[L. League]] Division 1\n* Amateur: Urawa Red Diamonds Amateur in Saitama Prefecture League Div. 1\n\n==Record==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n!Season\n!{{tooltip|Div.|Division}}\n!{{tooltip|Tms.|Teams}}\n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!{{tooltip|Avg. Attd.|Average Attendance}}\n![[Emperor's Cup]]\n![[J.League Cup]]\n![[Japanese Super Cup|Super Cup]]\n![[AFC Champions League|AFC CL]]\n!colspan=2|Others\n|-\n|1992\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|Semi-final\n|Group Stage\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|colspan=2|\u2013\n|-\n|[[1993 J.League|1993]]\n|J1\n|10\n|'''10'''\n|11,459\n|2nd round\n|Group Stage\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|colspan=2|\u2013\n|-\n|[[1994 J.League|1994]]\n|J1\n|12\n|'''12'''\n|18,475\n|3rd round\n|Quarter-final\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|colspan=2|\u2013\n|-\n|[[1995 J.League|1995]]\n|J1\n|14\n|'''4