i]] || {{flagu|Japan}} || April 2, 2018 \u2013 April 24, 2018 \n|-\n|[[Oswaldo de Oliveira]] || {{flagu|Brazil}} || April 25, 2018 \u2013 May 28, 2019\n|-\n|[[Tsuyoshi Otsuki]] || {{flagu|Japan}} || May 29, 2019 \u2013 \n|}\n\n==League history==\nExcepting two seasons in which they were in the second tier, Mitsubishi/Urawa has always competed in the top flight, thereby being the club with the most top flight seasons total.\n*'''Mitsubishi''' (Amateur era)\n**Division 1 (JSL and JSL Div.1) : 1965\u201366, 1988\u201389\n**Division 2 (JSL Div.2) : 1989\u201390\n**Division 1 (JSL Div.1) : 1990\u201391, 1991\u201392\n*'''Urawa Red Diamonds''' (professional era)\n**Division 1 (J.League) : 1993\u201399\n**Division 2 (J.League Div.2) : 2000\n**Division 1 (J.League Div.1) : 2001\u2013\n* Top scorer: [[Masahiro Fukuda]] with 152 goals\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.urawa-reds.co.jp  Urawa Red Diamonds official website] {{in lang|ja|en}}\n* [http://www.komura.com/urawa/  Urawa Red Diamonds Supporters Media website] (unofficial) {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Asian Champions League|Champions of Asia]]|before=[[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]]<br/>{{flagicon|South Korea}}|after=[[Gamba Osaka]]<br/>{{flagicon|Japan}}|years=[[2007 AFC Champions League|2007]]}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Asian Champions League|Champions of Asia]]|before=[[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]]<br/>{{flagicon|South Korea}}|after=[[Kashima Antlers]]<br/>{{flagicon|Japan}}|years=[[2017 AFC Champions League|2017]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Urawa Red Diamonds}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{J.League}}\n{{Japanese Club Football|group=clubs}}\n{{Japanese football champions}}\n{{Original Japan Soccer League clubs}}\n{{Original J.League clubs}}\n{{AFC Champions League winners}}\n{{AFC Club of the Year}}\n{{Saitama Sports}}\n{{J1 League champions}}\n{{J.League Cup champions}}\n{{Suruga Bank Championship winners}}\n{{Japan Professional Sports Grand Pr