{"title_page": "The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show", "text_new": "{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 8\n| episode        = 14\n| director       = [[Steven Dean Moore]]\n| writer         = [[David X. Cohen|David S. Cohen]]\n| production     = 4F12\n| airdate        = February 9, 1997\n| guests         = [[Alex Rocco]] as Roger Meyers, Jr.<br>[[Phil Hartman]] as [[Troy McClure]]\n| couch_gag      = A parody of the ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|Sgt. Pepper's]]'' album cover<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page14.shtml |title=The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |year=2000 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>{{Cref2|Note 1}}\n| commentary     = [[Matt Groening]]<BR>Josh Weinstein<BR>David X. Cohen<BR>[[Yeardley Smith]]<BR>Alex Rocco<BR>Steven Dean Moore\n| prev           = [[Simpsoncalifragilisticexpiala(Annoyed Grunt)cious]]\n| next           = [[Homer's Phobia]]\n}}\n\"'''The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show'''\" is the fourteenth episode in the [[The Simpsons (season 8)|eighth season]] of the American animated television series ''[[The Simpsons]]''. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on February 9, 1997.{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226\u2013227}} In the episode, ''[[The Itchy & Scratchy Show]]'' attempts to regain lost viewers by introducing a new character named Poochie, voiced by [[Homer Simpson|Homer]]. The episode is largely self-referential and satirizes the world of television production, fans of ''The Simpsons'', and the series itself. It was written by [[David X. Cohen]] and directed by [[Steven Dean Moore]]. [[Alex Rocco]] is a credited guest voice as [[List of recurring The Simpsons characters#Roger Meyers Jr.|Roger Meyers, Jr.]] for the third and final time (having previously provided the character's voice in \"[[Itchy & Scratchy & Marge]]\" and \"[[The Day the Violence Died]]\"); [[Phil Hartman]] also guest stars as [[Troy McClure]].{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226\u2013227}} Poochie would become a minor recurring character and [[Comic Book Guy]]'s catchphrase, \"Worst episode ever\", is introduced in this episode. With \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\", the show's 167th episode, ''The Simpsons'' surpassed ''[[The Flintstones]]'' in the number of episodes produced for a prime-time [[animated series]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[Krusty the Clown]] threatens to ditch ''[[The Itchy & Scratchy Show]]'' because the cartoon causes his ratings to nosedive during that segment of his show. Cartoon producer [[Itchy & Scratchy Show#Roger Meyers, Jr.|Roger Meyers]] convenes a [[focus group]] to discover why ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'' has lost its appeal. In the focus group, [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] explains that the show has lost its impact on audiences after being on the air for so long. \n\nMeyers decides that the cartoon needs a new character: Poochie, a dog with \"attitude\" who surfs, raps, and plays electric guitar. At [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and Lisa's suggestion, [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] auditions for Poochie's voice and gets the part. To promote Poochie, he and voice actor June Bellamy make several publicity stops, where they encounter the show's hardcore fans. Homer invites his friends and relatives to watch the first ''Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show''. However, the cartoon is full of asinine antics, with none of the show's flair or trademark violence. Unimpressed by the manic Poochie character, Homer's friends say little as they leave.\n\nMeyers decides to kill off Poochie, but Homer resolves to save him. At the next recording session, Homer goes off-script and implores the audience to give Poochie a chance. The show's production team appears moved by Homer's plea, but when the episode airs, Meyers has dubbed over Homer's voice: the new dialogue says that Poochie has \"died on the way back to his home planet\". The studio audience cheers as Krusty displays an [[affidavit]] swearing Poochie will never return. Homer feels betrayed but attributes the whole affair to the fickle nature of show business.\n\n==Production==\n\"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" was written by [[David X. Cohen]] and directed by [[Steven Dean Moore]].{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226\u2013227}} The episode was conceived as a commentary on what it was like to work on a television show that had long been on the air, but was considered to be nearing its end. This was intended to show that ''The Simpsons'' could still be good after eight seasons, even though it no longer had the \"shock value\" it did in the early years.<ref name=Cohencom>{{cite video |people=Cohen, David |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Before production of season eight began, several executives at Fox suggested the staff add a new character to the show, who would live with the Simpsons on a permanent basis, in a bid to freshen up the series.<ref name=Groeningcom>{{cite video |people=Groening, Matt |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cagle.msnbc.com/hogan/interviews/silverman.asp |title=Family Matters \u2013 The David Silverman Interview |work=[[MSNBC]] |author=Tom Heintjes |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217065814/http://cagle.msnbc.com/hogan/interviews/silverman.asp |archivedate=February 17, 2010}}</ref> The writers found the suggestion, usually considered a sign of desperation to boost a flagging series,<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\"/> amusing, therefore much of the episode revolves around this trope. Parallel to the episode's main plot, where Poochie is introduced on ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'' to boost its ratings, the writers inserted the one-time character Roy, a college-aged man who is shown to be living with the Simpsons, with no explanation as to his character or presence, as a reference to the executives' proposal.<ref name=Smithcom>{{cite video |people=Smith, Yeardley |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Roy was originally conceived for the \"Time and Punishment\" segment of the [[The Simpsons (season 6)|season six]] episode \"[[Treehouse of Horror V]]\", living with the Simpsons in one of the alternate realities,<ref name=Cohencom/> as a second, teenage son in the family.<ref name=\"Daniels\">{{cite video |people=Daniels, Greg |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Treehouse of Horror V\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nCohen's initial vision for Poochie was that he would be annoying to fans because he was wealthy, aloof and unlikeable. In the episode's DVD commentary he read his script for the first cartoon featuring Itchy, Scratchy, and Poochie:\n{{Cquote|Itchy and Scratchy are laborers in Poochie's gold mine. Poochie sits on a velvet throne surrounded by [[Money bag|bags of money]]. He drinks champagne as he whips Itchy and Scratchy and lectures them on the value of hard work in a capitalist society. Finally, Itchy and Scratchy get fed up and plan their revenge. They decide Scratchy will present a fake money bag to Poochie. Itchy will secretly be hiding in the bag. When Poochie raises the bag to inhale the sweet smell of money, Itchy will jab him in the nose with a syringe of poison. Itchy gets in the bag and Scratchy presents it to Poochie, but the plan backfires because Poochie is offended by how small the money bag is. To demonstrate how worthless it is to him, he sets it on fire and uses it to light his cigar. Itchy's flaming skeleton falls out of the burning bag, and the syringe lands on Scratchy's toe and kills him, too. Poochie says, \"Oh, well, I can always use my millions of dollars to hire more workers. That's the power of money.\" The end.<ref name=Cohencom/>}}\n\nAs with other episodes centering on the production of ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'', such as \"[[The Front (The Simpsons)|The Front]]\", the show's staff are shown. Almost all of them are based on the actual staff of ''The Simpsons''.<ref name=Cohencom/> In the first scene at the production table the person in the lower right corner, wearing a squid T-shirt, is Cohen. On the left side, the furthest away is [[Bill Oakley]] with [[Josh Weinstein]] next to him. Next to Weinstein is [[George Meyer]], who is the writer who speaks out and gets fired. The animator shown designing Poochie is supervising director [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]. As Silverman plays the [[tuba]], one was drawn into the background of the scene. Other writers who appear include [[Dan McGrath]], [[Ian Maxtone-Graham]], [[Donick Cary]], [[Ron Hauge]], [[Ned Goldreyer]], and [[Mike Scully]], who had to be added in later, as the animators did not have a photo to use as a likeness.<ref name=Cohencom/>\n\nThis episode also features the first use of [[Comic Book Guy]]'s catchphrase \"Worst. Episode. Ever.\", which was taken from the [[alt.tv.simpsons]] newsgroup.<ref name=Cohencom/>\n\n==Themes==\nThis episode saw ''The Simpsons'' surpass ''[[The Flintstones]]'' for the number of episodes produced for an [[animated series]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,290859,00.html |title=1997 Timeline |accessdate=March 13, 2007 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Marlene |last=McCampbell |date=December 26, 1997}}</ref> The episode therefore deals with the issue of longevity and the problems that arise when the producers try to make a show \"fresh\" again.<ref>Alberti, p. 143</ref> The show mainly deals with themes commonly known as \"[[jumping the shark]]\", instances that usually occur when a failing show adds a new character or major plot twist to boost ratings. The first theme is a commentary on adding a new character, when the show has run for too long. Usually, this is a technique used in shows that involve children who have grown up. This was the case with \"Oliver\" on ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'' and \"Luke Brower\" on ''[[Growing Pains]]''. The technique is also used in cartoons, notably with the addition of ''[[Scrappy-Doo]]'' to the ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' animated series ten years after its debut.<ref name=\"ScrappyDays\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsfromme.com/writings/scrappy-days/|title=Scrappy Days: The Birth of Scrappy-Doo and What I Had to Do with It |first=Mark|last=Evanier|authorlink=Mark Evanier|publisher=Newsfromme.com |date=|access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> Both Poochie and Roy are used to reflect this by attempting to keep ''The Itchy and Scratchy Show'' and the Simpson family fresh respectively.<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\">Alberti, p. 144</ref>\n\nAnother theme is the notion of network executives forcing ideas onto a show. The interaction between the writers and the network executives in the episode underscore the differences between them. The writers understand the show's inner workings, but the network executives approach improvements to the show from a business point of view. They try to incorporate what they see as a rebellious character with the comment \"This is popular with the kids\", but the viewers later reject the character.<ref>Alberti, pp. 145\u2013147</ref> The writers themselves are satirized in the episode, and are depicted as lazy and pretentious with few original ideas.{{sfn|Turner|2004|pp=297\u2013299}}\n\nThe last theme is the viewer backlash and obsession with internal consistency. When [[Comic Book Guy]] sees the Poochie episode, he immediately goes on the Internet and writes \"Worst episode ever\" on a message board; a commentary on how the active audience nit picks the episode. The writers respond by using the voice of Bart:<ref name=\"fans\">Alberti, pp. 147\u2013148</ref>\n\n:Bart: Hey, I know it wasn't great, but what right do you have to complain?\n:Comic Book Guy: As a loyal viewer, I feel they owe me.\n:Bart: What? They've given you thousands of hours of entertainment for free. What could they possibly owe you? I mean, if anything, ''you'' owe ''them''!\n:Comic Book Guy: ...Worst episode ever.\n\nEarlier in the episode, Homer and June Bellamy attend an in-store appearance as part of the promotion for the new character Poochie. They are asked a question of internal consistency, like the show's fans do all the time; Homer says to the fan who asks the question, \"Why would a man whose shirt says 'Genius at Work' spend all his time watching a children's cartoon show?\" This is again a reflection on how the writers feel about the fans obsessing about internal consistency.<ref name=\"fans\"/>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe original opening [[couch gag]] shows a [[pastiche]] of the cover collage from the [[The Beatles|Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', which was first used earlier in the season for \"[[Bart After Dark]]\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Otherwise, the episode refers to other TV shows, including the syndicated couch gag featuring the [[The Flintstones#The Flintstones|Flintstone family]], recycled from the [[The Simpsons (season 4)|season four]] episode \"[[Kamp Krusty]]\", to mark ''The Simpsons'' surpassing ''The Flintstones'' as the longest-running animated series.<ref name=\"IGNreview\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/883/883399p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" Review|first=Robert|last=Canning|date=2008-06-23|access-date=2008-06-23|website=[[IGN]]|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Roy calls Homer and Marge Mr. and Mrs. S, which echoes [[Fonzie]] calling the Cunninghams \"Mr. and Mrs. C\" on ''[[Happy Days]]''. Later, he decides to move in with \"two sexy ladies\", recalling [[Jack Tripper]] in ''[[Three's Company]]''.<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\"/> The backwards ball cap and untucked checkered shirt worn by Poochie or Roy closely resemble costuming used by the thematically similar ''[[Growing Pains]]'' character \"Luke Brower\".<ref name=\"gettyimages\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/in-vino-veritas-season-seven-9-28-91-jason-and-maggie-grew-news-photo/93765382|title=GROWING PAINS|date=1991-09-28|publisher=[[gettyimages]]|access-date=2019-04-11|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Homer hiding in the closet to hear what the network executives were planning to do with Poochie is a reference to [[Jay Leno]] reportedly eavesdropping on a conversation between [[NBC]] executives on whether he or [[David Letterman]] would replace [[Johnny Carson]] as the host of ''[[The Tonight Show]]''.<ref name=Weinstein>{{cite AV media|last=Weinstein|first=Josh|author-link=Josh Weinstein|date=2006|title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nItchy and Scratchy are based on ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' and other cat-and-mouse cartoons. As a boy, series creator [[Matt Groening]] and his friends would fantasize about an ultra-violent cartoon and how much fun it would be to work on a show like that.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Groening|first=Matt|author-link=Matt Groening|date=2002|title=The Simpsons season 2 DVD commentary for the episode \"Itchy & Scratchy & Marge\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> June Bellamy is a tribute to voice actress [[June Foray]].<ref name=Cohencom/> In the episode, Bellamy claims that she provided the \"[[Beep, beep (sound)|Beep, beep]]\" sound effect in the [[Wile E. Coyote and Road Runner]] cartoons; in reality the phrase was voiced by [[Paul Julian (artist)|Paul Julian]].<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Barrier|first=Michael|author-link=Michael Barrier (historian)|title=\"[[Fast and Furry-ous]]\" on [[Looney Tunes Golden Collection: Volume 1|Looney Tunes All-Stars: Part 1]] (Region 2 DVD release)|medium=DVD commentary|time=6m10s}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original American broadcast, \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" finished tied for 38th place in the weekly ratings for the week of February 3\u20139, 1997, with a Nielsen rating of 8.8. It was the third-highest-rated show on the Fox Network that week.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prime-Time Ratings |date=February 12, 1997 |page=F02 |newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]}}</ref>\n\nThis episode was placed 23rd on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s top 25 ''The Simpsons'' episodes list.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,417748_5,00.html |title=The Family Dynamic |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |date=January 29, 2003 |magazine=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, the authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', praised \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\", calling it \"a very neat episode which, like \"[[The Front (The Simpsons)|The Front]]\", is a good parody of the cartooning business.\" In 2007, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' named it the sixth-best episode in the show's history, describing it as \"a classic satire of network influence, obsessed TV fans, and programs that survive long after the shark has been jumped, the episode is a meta-celebration, a tongue-in-cheek rebuttal to everyone who claimed that the quality of ''The Simpsons'' had declined over the years.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first=John |last=Ortved |title=Springfield's Best |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=July 5, 2007|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2007/08/top10simpsons200708 |accessdate=July 13, 2007}}</ref> Todd Gilchrist called it a masterpiece, stating it \"could easily be packaged and sold by [itself]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.dvd.ign.com/articles/725/725343p1.html |title=The Simpsons \u2013 The Complete Eighth Season |accessdate=July 31, 2007 |first=Todd |last=Gilchrist |date=August 14, 2006 |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref> ''[[Planet Simpson]]'' author Chris Turner describes the episode as \"the most contentious and direct counterattack ''The Simpsons'' ever unleashed on its fans\"{{sfn|Turner|2004|pp=297\u2013299}} and \"[harsh] satire of the working world of big-time TV production\".{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=419}} Robert Canning of ''[[IGN]]'' said it was \"laugh-out-loud funny\" and describing the introduction of Roy as \"a hilarious parody of a classic, overused television device.\"<ref name=\"IGNreview\" /> [[Alan Sepinwall]] of ''[[The Star Ledger]]'', in a review printed two days after the episode originally aired, praised the writers for not airing a \"very special\" episode to celebrate the milestone of overtaking ''The Flintstones''. He noted \"[the episode is] so self-aware it put the best in-jokes on ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'' to shame.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Simpsons' as slyly subversive as ever |date=February 11, 1997 |newspaper=[[The Star Ledger]] |page=43 |author=Alan Sepinwall}}</ref> The [[BBC]] named it as one of the ten most memorable episodes of the show, noting, \"the writers used the opportunity to pay tribute to the art of animation and rail against network interference in their show.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons: 10 classic episodes |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/entertainment/8449416.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=January 14, 2010 |accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' ranked the episode second in its list of 10 best ''Simpsons'' episodes picked by ''Simpsons'' experts.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Raisa Bruner |title=We Asked Experts for 10 of Their Most Memorable Simpsons Episodes of All Time |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=2019-12-10 |url=https://time.com/5743465/best-simpsons-episodes/|accessdate=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''The Simpsons'' writers picked \"The Beagle Has Landed\" as one of their nine favorite \"Itchy & Stratchy\" episodes of all time.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons\u2019 Writers Pick Their Favorite \u2018Itchy & Scratchy\u2019 Cartoons |url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/simpsons-writers-favorite-itchy-and-scratchy-cartoons.html |publisher=[[Vulture (blog)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=March 26, 2014 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nComic Book Guy's phrase \"Worst. Episode. Ever\" was named by ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' as a quote that could be used in everyday life, as well as being one of the most popular quotes from the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/beyond-doh-simpsons-quotes-for-everyday-use-1543 |title=Beyond \"D'oh!\": Simpsons Quotes For Everyday Use |author=Bahn, Christopher; Donna Bowman, Josh Modell, Noel Murray, Nathan Rabin, Tasha Robinson, Kyle Ryan, Scott Tobias |lastauthoramp=yes |date=April 26, 2006 |accessdate=August 8, 2017 |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Cnote2 Begin}}\n{{Cnote2|Note 1|In [[broadcast syndication|syndication]], this is replaced with the couch gag from the [[The Simpsons (season 4)|season four]] episode \"[[Kamp Krusty]]\" which parodies ''[[The Flintstones]]'', but the audio from the original couch gag remains.<ref name=\"IGNreview\" />}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Alberti |first=John (ed.) |year=2003 |title=Leaving Springfield: \"The Simpsons\" and the Possibility of Oppositional Culture |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=0-8143-2849-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/leavingspringfie00albe }}\n*{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]]  |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Turner |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Turner (author) |title=[[Planet Simpson|Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Documented an Era and Defined a Generation]] |others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]. |edition=1st |year=2004 |location=Toronto |publisher=[[Random House Canada]] |oclc=55682258 |isbn=978-0-679-31318-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_8#The_Itchy_.26_Scratchy_.26_Poochie_Show|\"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"}}\n{{portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-14 \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{Snpp capsule|4F12}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/the-itchy-and-scratchy-and-poochie-show-1452}}\n*{{imdb episode|0701245}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|8}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Itchy and Scratchy and Poochie Show, The}}\n[[Category:1997 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 8) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by David X. Cohen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 8\n| episode        = 14\n| director       = [[Steven Dean Moore]]\n| writer         = [[David X. Cohen|David S. Cohen]]\n| production     = 4F12\n| airdate        = February 9, 1997\n| guests         = [[Alex Rocco]] as Roger Meyers, Jr.<br>[[Phil Hartman]] as [[Troy McClure]]\n| couch_gag      = A parody of the ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|Sgt. Pepper's]]'' album cover<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page14.shtml |title=The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |year=2000 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>{{Cref2|Note 1}}\n| commentary     = [[Matt Groening]]<BR>Josh Weinstein<BR>David X. Cohen<BR>[[Yeardley Smith]]<BR>Alex Rocco<BR>Steven Dean Moore\n| prev           = [[Simpsoncalifragilisticexpiala(Annoyed Grunt)cious]]\n| next           = [[Homer's Phobia]]\n}}\n\"'''The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show'''\" is the fourteenth episode in the [[The Simpsons (season 8)|eighth season]] of the American animated television series ''[[The Simpsons]]''. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on February 9, 1997.{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226-227}} In the episode, ''[[The Itchy & Scratchy Show]]'' attempts to regain lost viewers by introducing a new character named Poochie, voiced by [[Homer Simpson|Homer]]. The episode is largely self-referential and satirizes the world of television production, fans of ''The Simpsons'', and the series itself. It was written by [[David X. Cohen]] and directed by [[Steven Dean Moore]]. [[Alex Rocco]] is a credited guest voice as [[List of recurring The Simpsons characters#Roger Meyers Jr.|Roger Meyers, Jr.]] for the third and final time (having previously provided the character's voice in \"[[Itchy & Scratchy & Marge]]\" and \"[[The Day the Violence Died]]\"); [[Phil Hartman]] also guest stars as [[Troy McClure]].{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226-227}} Poochie would become a minor recurring character and [[Comic Book Guy]]'s catchphrase, \"Worst episode ever\", is introduced in this episode. With \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\", the show's 167th episode, ''The Simpsons'' surpassed ''[[The Flintstones]]'' in the number of episodes produced for a prime-time [[animated series]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[Krusty the Clown]] threatens to ditch ''[[The Itchy & Scratchy Show]]'' because the cartoon causes his ratings to nosedive during that segment of his show. Cartoon producer [[Itchy & Scratchy Show#Roger Meyers, Jr.|Roger Meyers]] convenes a [[focus group]] to discover why ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'' has lost its appeal. In the focus group, [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] explains that the show has lost its impact on audiences after being on the air for so long. \n\nMeyers decides that the cartoon needs a new character: Poochie, a dog with \"attitude\" who surfs, raps, and plays electric guitar. At [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and Lisa's suggestion, [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] auditions for Poochie's voice and gets the part. To promote Poochie, he and voice actor June Bellamy make several publicity stops, where they encounter the show's hardcore fans. Homer invites his friends and relatives to watch the first ''Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show''. However, the cartoon is full of asinine antics, with none of the show's flair or trademark violence. Unimpressed by the manic Poochie character, Homer's friends say little as they leave.\n\nMeyers decides to kill off Poochie, but Homer resolves to save him. At the next recording session, Homer goes off-script and implores the audience to give Poochie a chance. The show's production team appears moved by Homer's plea, but when the episode airs, Meyers has dubbed over Homer's voice: the new dialogue says that Poochie has \"died on the way back to his home planet\". The studio audience cheers as Krusty displays an [[affidavit]] swearing Poochie will never return. Homer feels betrayed but attributes the whole affair to the fickle nature of show business.\n\n==Production==\n\"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" was written by [[David X. Cohen]] and directed by [[Steven Dean Moore]].{{sfn|Richmond & Coffman|1997 |pp=226-227}} The episode was conceived as a commentary on what it was like to work on a television show that had long been on the air, but was considered to be nearing its end. This was intended to show that ''The Simpsons'' could still be good after eight seasons, even though it no longer had the \"shock value\" it did in the early years.<ref name=Cohencom>{{cite video |people=Cohen, David |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Before production of season eight began, several executives at Fox suggested the staff add a new character to the show, who would live with the Simpsons on a permanent basis, in a bid to freshen up the series.<ref name=Groeningcom>{{cite video |people=Groening, Matt |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cagle.msnbc.com/hogan/interviews/silverman.asp |title=Family Matters - The David Silverman Interview |work=[[MSNBC]] |author=Tom Heintjes |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217065814/http://cagle.msnbc.com/hogan/interviews/silverman.asp |archivedate=February 17, 2010}}</ref> The writers found the suggestion, usually considered a sign of desperation to boost a flagging series,<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\"/> amusing, therefore much of the episode revolves around this trope. Parallel to the episode's main plot, where Poochie is introduced on ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'' to boost its ratings, the writers inserted the one-time character Roy, a college-aged man who is shown to be living with the Simpsons, with no explanation as to his character or presence, as a reference to the executives' proposal.<ref name=Smithcom>{{cite video |people=Smith, Yeardley |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Roy was originally conceived for the \"Time and Punishment\" segment of the [[The Simpsons (season 6)|season six]] episode \"[[Treehouse of Horror V]]\", living with the Simpsons in one of the alternate realities,<ref name=Cohencom/> as a second, teenage son in the family.<ref name=\"Daniels\">{{cite video |people=Daniels, Greg |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons The Complete Sixth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"Treehouse of Horror V\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nCohen's initial vision for Poochie was that he would be annoying to fans because he was wealthy, aloof and unlikeable. In the episode's DVD commentary he read his script for the first cartoon featuring Itchy, Scratchy, and Poochie:\n{{Cquote|Itchy and Scratchy are laborers in Poochie's gold mine. Poochie sits on a velvet throne surrounded by [[Money bag|bags of money]]. He drinks champagne as he whips Itchy and Scratchy and lectures them on the value of hard work in a capitalist society. Finally, Itchy and Scratchy get fed up and plan their revenge. They decide Scratchy will present a fake money bag to Poochie. Itchy will secretly be hiding in the bag. When Poochie raises the bag to inhale the sweet smell of money, Itchy will jab him in the nose with a syringe of poison. Itchy gets in the bag and Scratchy presents it to Poochie, but the plan backfires because Poochie is offended by how small the money bag is. To demonstrate how worthless it is to him, he sets it on fire and uses it to light his cigar. Itchy's flaming skeleton falls out of the burning bag, and the syringe lands on Scratchy's toe and kills him, too. Poochie says, \"Oh, well, I can always use my millions of dollars to hire more workers. That's the power of money.\" The end.<ref name=Cohencom/>}}\n\nAs with other episodes centering on the production of ''The Itchy & Scratchy Show'', such as \"[[The Front (The Simpsons)|The Front]]\", the show's staff are shown. Almost all of them are based on the actual staff of ''The Simpsons''.<ref name=Cohencom/> In the first scene at the production table the person in the lower right corner, wearing a squid T-shirt, is Cohen. On the left side, the furthest away is [[Bill Oakley]] with [[Josh Weinstein]] next to him. Next to Weinstein is [[George Meyer]], who is the writer who speaks out and gets fired. The animator shown designing Poochie is supervising director [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]. As Silverman plays the [[tuba]], one was drawn into the background of the scene. Other writers who appear include [[Dan McGrath]], [[Ian Maxtone-Graham]], [[Donick Cary]], [[Ron Hauge]], [[Ned Goldreyer]], and [[Mike Scully]], who had to be added in later, as the animators did not have a photo to use as a likeness.<ref name=Cohencom/>\n\nThis episode also features the first use of [[Comic Book Guy]]'s catchphrase \"Worst. Episode. Ever.\", which was taken from the [[alt.tv.simpsons]] newsgroup.<ref name=Cohencom/>\n\n==Themes==\nThis episode saw ''The Simpsons'' surpass ''[[The Flintstones]]'' for the number of episodes produced for an [[animated series]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,290859,00.html |title=1997 Timeline |accessdate=March 13, 2007 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Marlene |last=McCampbell |date=December 26, 1997}}</ref> The episode therefore deals with the issue of longevity and the problems that arise when the producers try to make a show \"fresh\" again.<ref>Alberti, p. 143</ref> The show mainly deals with themes commonly known as \"[[jumping the shark]]\", instances that usually occur when a failing show adds a new character or major plot twist to boost ratings. The first theme is a commentary on adding a new character, when the show has run for too long. Usually, this is a technique used in shows that involve children who have grown up. This was the case with \"Oliver\" on ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'' and \"Luke Brower\" on ''[[Growing Pains]]''. The technique is also used in cartoons, notably with the addition of ''[[Scrappy-Doo]]'' to the ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' animated series ten years after its debut.<ref name=\"ScrappyDays\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsfromme.com/writings/scrappy-days/|title=Scrappy Days: The Birth of Scrappy-Doo and What I Had to Do with It |first=Mark|last=Evanier|authorlink=Mark Evanier|publisher=Newsfromme.com |date=|access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> Both Poochie and Roy are used to reflect this by attempting to keep ''The Itchy and Scratchy Show'' and the Simpson family fresh respectively.<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\">Alberti, p. 144</ref>\n\nAnother theme is the notion of network executives forcing ideas onto a show. The interaction between the writers and the network executives in the episode underscore the differences between them. The writers understand the show's inner workings, but the network executives approach improvements to the show from a business point of view. They try to incorporate what they see as a rebellious character with the comment \"This is popular with the kids\", but the viewers later reject the character.<ref>Alberti, pp. 145-147</ref> The writers themselves are satirized in the episode, and are depicted as lazy and pretentious with few original ideas.{{sfn|Turner|2004|pp=297-299}}\n\nThe last theme is the viewer backlash and obsession with internal consistency. When [[Comic Book Guy]] sees the Poochie episode, he immediately goes on the Internet and writes \"Worst episode ever\" on a message board; a commentary on how the active audience nit picks the episode. The writers respond by using the voice of Bart:<ref name=\"fans\">Alberti, pp. 147-148</ref>\n\n:Bart: Hey, I know it wasn't great, but what right do you have to complain?\n:Comic Book Guy: As a loyal viewer, I feel they owe me.\n:Bart: What? They've given you thousands of hours of entertainment for free. What could they possibly owe you? I mean, if anything, ''you'' owe ''them''!\n:Comic Book Guy: ...Worst episode ever.\n\nEarlier in the episode, Homer and June Bellamy attend an in-store appearance as part of the promotion for the new character Poochie. They are asked a question of internal consistency, like the show's fans do all the time; Homer says to the fan who asks the question, \"Why would a man whose shirt says 'Genius at Work' spend all his time watching a children's cartoon show?\" This is again a reflection on how the writers feel about the fans obsessing about internal consistency.<ref name=\"fans\"/>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe original opening [[couch gag]] shows a [[pastiche]] of the cover collage from the [[The Beatles|Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', which was first used earlier in the season for \"[[Bart After Dark]]\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Otherwise, the episode refers to other TV shows, including the syndicated couch gag featuring the [[The Flintstones#The Flintstones|Flintstone family]], recycled from the [[The Simpsons (season 4)|season four]] episode \"[[Kamp Krusty]]\", to mark ''The Simpsons'' surpassing ''The Flintstones'' as the longest-running animated series.<ref name=\"IGNreview\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/883/883399p1.html|title=The Simpsons Flashback: \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" Review|first=Robert|last=Canning|date=2008-06-23|access-date=2008-06-23|website=[[IGN]]|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Roy calls Homer and Marge Mr. and Mrs. S, which echoes [[Fonzie]] calling the Cunninghams \"Mr. and Mrs. C\" on ''[[Happy Days]]''. Later, he decides to move in with \"two sexy ladies\", recalling [[Jack Tripper]] in ''[[Three's Company]]''.<ref name=\"Alberti, p. 144\"/> The backwards ball cap and untucked checkered shirt worn by Poochie or Roy closely resemble costuming used by the thematically similar ''[[Growing Pains]]'' character \"Luke Brower\".<ref name=\"gettyimages\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/in-vino-veritas-season-seven-9-28-91-jason-and-maggie-grew-news-photo/93765382|title=GROWING PAINS|date=1991-09-28|publisher=[[gettyimages]]|access-date=2019-04-11|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Homer hiding in the closet to hear what the network executives were planning to do with Poochie is a reference to [[Jay Leno]] reportedly eavesdropping on a conversation between [[NBC]] executives on whether he or [[David Letterman]] would replace [[Johnny Carson]] as the host of ''[[The Tonight Show]]''.<ref name=Weinstein>{{cite AV media|last=Weinstein|first=Josh|author-link=Josh Weinstein|date=2006|title=The Simpsons The Complete Eighth Season DVD commentary for the episode \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nItchy and Scratchy are based on ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' and other cat-and-mouse cartoons. As a boy, series creator [[Matt Groening]] and his friends would fantasize about an ultra-violent cartoon and how much fun it would be to work on a show like that.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Groening|first=Matt|author-link=Matt Groening|date=2002|title=The Simpsons season 2 DVD commentary for the episode \"Itchy & Scratchy & Marge\"|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> June Bellamy is a tribute to voice actress [[June Foray]].<ref name=Cohencom/> In the episode, Bellamy claims that she provided the \"[[Beep, beep (sound)|Beep, beep]]\" sound effect in the [[Wile E. Coyote and Road Runner]] cartoons; in reality the phrase was voiced by [[Paul Julian (artist)|Paul Julian]].<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Barrier|first=Michael|author-link=Michael Barrier (historian)|title=\"[[Fast and Furry-ous]]\" on [[Looney Tunes Golden Collection: Volume 1|Looney Tunes All-Stars: Part 1]] (Region 2 DVD release)|medium=DVD commentary|time=6m10s}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original American broadcast, \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\" finished tied for 38th place in the weekly ratings for the week of February 3\u20139, 1997, with a Nielsen rating of 8.8. It was the third-highest-rated show on the Fox Network that week.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prime-Time Ratings |date=February 12, 1997 |page=F02 |newspaper=[[The Orange County Register]]}}</ref>\n\nThis episode was placed 23rd on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s top 25 ''The Simpsons'' episodes list.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,417748_5,00.html |title=The Family Dynamic |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |date=January 29, 2003 |magazine=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, the authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', praised \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\", calling it \"a very neat episode which, like \"[[The Front (The Simpsons)|The Front]]\", is a good parody of the cartooning business.\" In 2007, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' named it the sixth-best episode in the show's history, describing it as \"a classic satire of network influence, obsessed TV fans, and programs that survive long after the shark has been jumped, the episode is a meta-celebration, a tongue-in-cheek rebuttal to everyone who claimed that the quality of ''The Simpsons'' had declined over the years.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first=John |last=Ortved |title=Springfield's Best |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=July 5, 2007|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2007/08/top10simpsons200708 |accessdate=July 13, 2007}}</ref> Todd Gilchrist called it a masterpiece, stating it \"could easily be packaged and sold by [itself]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.dvd.ign.com/articles/725/725343p1.html |title=The Simpsons - The Complete Eighth Season |accessdate=July 31, 2007 |first=Todd |last=Gilchrist |date=August 14, 2006 |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref> ''[[Planet Simpson]]'' author Chris Turner describes the episode as \"the most contentious and direct counterattack ''The Simpsons'' ever unleashed on its fans\"{{sfn|Turner|2004|pp=297-299}} and \"[harsh] satire of the working world of big-time TV production\".{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=419}} Robert Canning of ''[[IGN]]'' said it was \"laugh-out-loud funny\" and describing the introduction of Roy as \"a hilarious parody of a classic, overused television device.\"<ref name=\"IGNreview\" /> [[Alan Sepinwall]] of ''[[The Star Ledger]]'', in a review printed two days after the episode originally aired, praised the writers for not airing a \"very special\" episode to celebrate the milestone of overtaking ''The Flintstones''. He noted \"[the episode is] so self-aware it put the best in-jokes on ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'' to shame.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Simpsons' as slyly subversive as ever |date=February 11, 1997 |newspaper=[[The Star Ledger]] |page=43 |author=Alan Sepinwall}}</ref> The [[BBC]] named it as one of the ten most memorable episodes of the show, noting, \"the writers used the opportunity to pay tribute to the art of animation and rail against network interference in their show.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons: 10 classic episodes |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/entertainment/8449416.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=January 14, 2010 |accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' ranked the episode second in its list of 10 best ''Simpsons'' episodes picked by ''Simpsons'' experts.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Raisa Bruner |title=We Asked Experts for 10 of Their Most Memorable Simpsons Episodes of All Time |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=2019-12-10 |url=https://time.com/5743465/best-simpsons-episodes/|accessdate=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''The Simpsons'' writers picked \"The Beagle Has Landed\" as one of their nine favorite \"Itchy & Stratchy\" episodes of all time.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons\u2019 Writers Pick Their Favorite \u2018Itchy & Scratchy\u2019 Cartoons |url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/simpsons-writers-favorite-itchy-and-scratchy-cartoons.html |publisher=[[Vulture (blog)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |date=March 26, 2014 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nComic Book Guy's phrase \"Worst. Episode. Ever\" was named by ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' as a quote that could be used in everyday life, as well as being one of the most popular quotes from the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/beyond-doh-simpsons-quotes-for-everyday-use-1543 |title=Beyond \"D'oh!\": Simpsons Quotes For Everyday Use |author=Bahn, Christopher; Donna Bowman, Josh Modell, Noel Murray, Nathan Rabin, Tasha Robinson, Kyle Ryan, Scott Tobias |lastauthoramp=yes |date=April 26, 2006 |accessdate=August 8, 2017 |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Cnote2 Begin}}\n{{Cnote2|Note 1|In [[broadcast syndication|syndication]], this is replaced with the couch gag from the [[The Simpsons (season 4)|season four]] episode \"[[Kamp Krusty]]\" which parodies ''[[The Flintstones]]'', but the audio from the original couch gag remains.<ref name=\"IGNreview\" />}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Alberti |first=John (ed.) |year=2003 |title=Leaving Springfield: \"The Simpsons\" and the Possibility of Oppositional Culture |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=0-8143-2849-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/leavingspringfie00albe }}\n*{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]]  |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Turner |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Turner (author) |title=[[Planet Simpson|Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Documented an Era and Defined a Generation]] |others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]. |edition=1st |year=2004 |location=Toronto |publisher=[[Random House Canada]] |oclc=55682258 |isbn=978-0-679-31318-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_8#The_Itchy_.26_Scratchy_.26_Poochie_Show|\"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"}}\n{{portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-14 \"The Itchy & Scratchy & Poochie Show\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{Snpp capsule|4F12}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/the-itchy-and-scratchy-and-poochie-show-1452}}\n*{{imdb episode|0701245}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|8}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Itchy and Scratchy and Poochie Show, The}}\n[[Category:1997 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 8) episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by David X. Cohen]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Itchy_%26_Scratchy_%26_Poochie_Show"}
{"title_page": "Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Twice Upon a Time (''Doctor Who'')}}\n{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 276\n| serial_name        = Twice Upon a Time\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| doctors            =\n* [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n* [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] ([[First Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Pearl Mackie]] ([[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]])\n| guests             = \n* [[Mark Gatiss]] \u2013 The Captain\n* [[Jenna Coleman]] \u2013 [[Clara Oswald|Clara]]\n* [[Matt Lucas]] \u2013 [[Nardole]]\n* [[Nikki Amuka-Bird]] \u2013 Helen Clay\n* [[Toby Whithouse]] \u2013 German Soldier\n* [[Lily Travers]] \u2013 [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]]\n* Jared Garfield \u2013 [[Ben Jackson (Doctor Who)|Ben Jackson]]\n* [[Nicholas Briggs]] \u2013 Voice of the [[Daleks]]\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] \u2013 [[Thirteenth Doctor|The Doctor]]\n| director           = [[Rachel Talalay]]\n| writer             = [[Steven Moffat]]\n| producer           = [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]]\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat<br>Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| length             = 60 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2017|12|25|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\"\n| following          = \"[[The Woman Who Fell to Earth]]\"\n}}\n\n\"'''Twice Upon a Time'''\" is an episode of the British [[Science fiction on television|science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', written by [[Steven Moffat]], directed by [[Rachel Talalay]], and was broadcast as the thirteenth [[List of Doctor Who Christmas specials|Christmas special]] on 25 December 2017 on [[BBC One]]. It features the final regular appearance of [[Peter Capaldi]] as the [[Twelfth Doctor]], the first official appearance of [[Jodie Whittaker]] as the [[Thirteenth Doctor]], and guest-stars [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] as the [[First Doctor]], having previously portrayed original First Doctor actor [[William Hartnell]] in the 2013 docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''. [[Pearl Mackie]] guest stars as the Twelfth Doctor's former companion [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]], while his other companions make guest appearances \u2013\n[[Jenna Coleman]] as [[Clara Oswald]] and [[Matt Lucas]] as [[Nardole]].\n\nThis episode is a continuation of events after \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", addressing the cliffhanger that it ended on, and takes place during the final story of the [[First Doctor]]; footage from the 1966 serial ''[[The Tenth Planet]]'', is used in the special. \"Twice Upon a Time\" is Capaldi's fourth and final Christmas special as the Twelfth Doctor, and the last ''Doctor Who'' story to be written and produced by Moffat, who had served as the show's executive producer and chief writer since taking over from [[Russell T Davies]] in 2010. After the special's broadcast, Moffat was succeeded as executive producer and showrunner by [[Chris Chibnall]]. It is also the last episode to have music composed by [[Murray Gold]], who had composed music for Doctor Who since the series' revival in 2005. From [[Doctor Who (series 11)|series 11]], music was composed by [[Segun Akinola]].\n\nThe special has received generally positive reviews from critics, with some criticism has been directed towards the episode's representation of the First Doctor.\n\n==Plot==\n=== Synopsis ===\nWandering back to his [[TARDIS]] through the South Pole in 1986 after leaving his companions behind, the [[First Doctor]] refuses to [[Regeneration (Doctor Who)|regenerate]]. He encounters the [[Twelfth Doctor]] outside his own TARDIS in a similar state of mind. The pair are soon approached by a confused and injured [[World War I|First World War]] British captain, displaced from December 1914 while in a gun-point stalemate with a German soldier. All three are then forcibly taken into a large spaceship. Inside, they meet with [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill]]; the Twelfth Doctor, however, doubts she is the real Bill. Upon encountering the ship's glass-like [[Holography|holographic]] pilot, they are offered freedom in exchange for allowing the ship to return the Captain to the moment of his death. Refusing to allow the Captain to die, they escape and take the First Doctor's TARDIS to the planet Villengard in the far future.\n\nAlone, the Twelfth Doctor meets with the rogue Dalek [[Into the Dalek|Rusty]], who has taken refuge from other Daleks hunting it. Given access to the Dalek Hivemind, the Doctor learns that the pilot and its ship, known as ''Testimony'', were created on New Earth, designed to extract people from their timelines at the moment of their death, and archive their memories into glass avatars. \"Bill\" is one such avatar, created from her memories. Seeing no evil to fight, the Doctors agree to return the Captain to his timeline. Upon arrival, the Captain asks the Doctors to keep an eye on his family, introducing himself as Archibald Hamish Lethbridge-Stewart, implying that he is the ancestor of the Doctor's frequent ally and lifelong friend the [[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart|Brigadier]].  As time resumes, the Doctors watch as soldiers on both sides begin singing \"[[Silent Night]]\". The Twelfth Doctor explains to the First that he deliberately shifted the Captain's timeline to the start of the [[Christmas truce]], to ensure his life would be spared.\n\nWith the Captain saved, the First Doctor informs the Twelfth that he is prepared to regenerate and says his goodbyes before returning to his TARDIS. Now alone with Bill's avatar, the Twelfth Doctor adamantly contends she is not really Bill, but she argues that memories are what define a person. Bill's avatar restores the Doctor's memories of [[Clara Oswald]] before they are joined by [[Nardole]]'s avatar. The Doctor, however, refuses to give the avatars testimony of his life. They respect his wish to be alone and leave after he embraces them both. The Doctor then returns to the TARDIS and decides it's now time to regenerate, but not before relaying advice to his next incarnation.\n\nAfter the newly regenerated [[Thirteenth Doctor]] examines her reflection, the TARDIS suffers multiple system failures due to damage caused by the delayed regeneration. Falling out of the tumbling ship, the Doctor watches in horror as the time rotor and the console room explode, and the TARDIS dematerialises while she plummets towards the Earth below.\n\n=== Continuity ===\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" takes place towards the end of the First Doctor's final serial, ''[[The Tenth Planet]]'' (first broadcast in October 1966), some of which is shown at the start of the special. During the last episode's final moments, the Doctor leaves his companions [[Ben Jackson (Doctor Who)|Ben]] and [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]] and returns to the TARDIS; they find him collapsed in the console room, where he undergoes his first regeneration. [[Derek Martinus]], the episode's director, reportedly cut a line from the original script which suggested that the Doctor was refusing to give in to the regeneration process. Steven Moffat's 2017 story creates an extended narrative around that part of the story, in which the First Doctor delays his regeneration and encounters his future self \u2014 the Twelfth Doctor \u2014 in the snowy wasteland.<ref name=\"denofgeek\">{{cite web|last1=Dillon-Trenchard|first1=Peter|title=Doctor Who: geeky spots & references in Twice Upon A Time|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/twice-upon-a-time/54180/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|website=Den of Geek|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226193632/http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/twice-upon-a-time/54180/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|archivedate=26 December 2017|language=en|date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-martin\">{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Daniel|title=Doctor Who Christmas special 2017: Twice Upon a Time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-2017-twice-upon-a-time|website=The Guardian|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226194106/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-2017-twlewice-upon-a-time|archivedate=26 December 2017|date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Testimony shows the First Doctor images of his future incarnations, clips from both the classic series and the revival are used, including the [[Third Doctor]] from ''[[Invasion of the Dinosaurs]]'' (1974); the [[Fifth Doctor]] from ''[[Arc of Infinity]]'' (1983); the [[Seventh Doctor]] from ''[[The Happiness Patrol]]'' (1988); the [[Eighth Doctor]] from \"[[The Night of the Doctor]]\" (2013); the [[Ninth Doctor]] from \"[[The Parting of the Ways]]\" (2005); and the [[Tenth Doctor]] from \"[[The Waters of Mars]]\" (2009).<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nTestimony also lists several of the Doctor's future titles: \"The Shadow of the [[Valeyard]]\" (from ''[[The Trial of a Time Lord]]'', said to be a distillation of the Doctor's darker side), \"the Oncoming Storm\" (\"The Parting of the Ways\"), \"the Imp of the Pandorica\" (a reference to the [[Eleventh Doctor]] story \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\"), \"the Beast of Trenzalore\" (\"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\"), \"the Butcher of Skull Moon\" and \"the Doctor of War\" (\"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\"). \"The Destroyer of Skaro\" refers to the destruction of the planet in ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (1988), although [[Skaro]] was later restored and rebuilt; as explained in \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012) and shown in \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\" (2015).<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/>\n\nThe Weapons Factories of Villengard were originally mentioned in \"[[The Doctor Dances]]\" ([[Steven Moffat]]'s first ''Doctor Who'' story), where the Ninth Doctor implied that he was responsible for their destruction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-25/doctor-who-christmas-special-set-visit/|title=19 things we learned from the set of the Doctor Who Christmas special|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-06/theres-a-subtle-callback-to-steven-moffats-very-first-doctor-who-story-in-the-christmas-special/|title=There's a subtle callback to Steven Moffat's very first Doctor Who story in the Christmas special|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHelen Clay, who would become Testimony's glass pilot, was from New Earth and lectured at \"New Earth University,\" a reference to the Tenth Doctor stories [[New Earth (Doctor Who)|New Earth]] and [[Gridlock (Doctor Who)|Gridlock]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trenchard |first1=Pete |title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-easter-eggs-and-references-in-twice-upon-a-time |website=denofgeek.com |accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Outside references ===\nThe Doctor addresses his original incarnation as \"[[Mary Berry]]\", \"[[Lance Corporal Jones|Corporal Jones]]\", and \"Mr Pastry\".<ref name=\"denofgeek.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-easter-eggs-and-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> Mr Pastry was a comedic variety stage act and children's show character played by actor [[Richard Hearne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/changingwho/10303.shtml?page=9|title=BBC \u2013 Archive \u2013 The Changing Face of Doctor Who \u2013 Nearly Who|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> who was once considered for the role of the [[Fourth Doctor]]. Hearne, however, wanted to play the Doctor as a version of Mr. Pastry, so he was passed over in favour of [[Tom Baker]].<ref name=\"denofgeek.com1\"/>\n\nThe Doctor paraphrases philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]] when he advises his future self that \"hate is always foolish and love is always wise\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-time-gentlemen-now-its-jodies-turn|title=Doctor Who Christmas special review \u2013 time, gentlemen. Now it's Jodie's turn|last=Wollaston|first=Sam|date=2017-12-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n=== Cast notes ===\n[[Peter Capaldi]] reprised his role as the [[Twelfth Doctor]]. On 30 January 2017, he confirmed that the tenth series would be his last, and that he was set to leave after the 2017 Christmas special.<ref name=\"CapaldiLeaving\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/43787cd6-f1de-4264-a509-d387d9a89c4b|title=Peter Capaldi announces he will stand down as Doctor Who at the end of the year|work=[[BBC]]|date=30 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> The episode also sees the introduction of [[Jodie Whittaker]] as the [[Thirteenth Doctor]], whose casting was announced on 16 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40608669|title=Doctor Who: New actor to be revealed after Wimbledon|work=[[BBC]]|date=14 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ThirteenthDoctorCasting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/16/doctor-jodie-whittaker-replace-peter-capaldi-time-lord-regeneration/ |title=Doctor Who: Jodie Whittaker is to replace Peter Capaldi in the Time Lord regeneration game |work=The Telegraph |date=16 July 2017 |accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who).jpg|thumb|250px|right|David Bradley's performance as the First Doctor was praised by critics.]]\nDavid Bradley appears in the episode as the First Doctor, having previously portrayed [[William Hartnell]] in the docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/4v2JXlkFdw3zvl6KF0fhgzX/the-doctor-falls-the-fact-file|title=Series 10, Doctor Who \u2013 The Doctor Falls: The Fact File \u2013 BBC One|website=BBC|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/01/first-look-pictures-first-twelfth-doctors-together-doctor-christmas/ |title=First look pictures of the First and Twelfth Doctors together in the Doctor Who Christmas special |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-02/new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures-tease-history-making-reunion-for-peter-capaldis-doctor |title=New Doctor Who Christmas special pictures tease history-making reunion for Peter Capaldi's Doctor |first=James |last=Gill |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref> This makes him the third actor to play the role in the television programme, after William Hartnell and [[Richard Hurndall]] (in 1983's ''[[The Five Doctors]]'') since the premiere of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jul/01/doctor-who-recap-series-36-finale-the-doctor-falls |title=Doctor Who recap: series 36 finale \u2013 The Doctor Falls |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Guardian}}</ref> Bradley previously played Solomon in the 2012 episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\". Since 2017, Bradley has reprised his role as the First Doctor in many audio dramas for [[Big Finish Productions]] alongside his co-stars from ''An Adventure in Space and Time''.\n\nThe first trailer for the episode was shown during the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], revealing the return of [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]], a companion from the end of [[William Hartnell]]'s tenure as the [[First Doctor]], portrayed by [[Lily Travers]],<ref name=\"Region1\" /> and [[Pearl Mackie]] as [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]]. Also confirmed were appearances by [[Toby Whithouse]], writer of seven episodes between 2006 and 2017,<ref name =\"breakdown\">{{cite web |url= http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/doctor-who-2017-christmas-special-twice-upon-a-time-trailer-breakdown |title= Doctor Who 2017 Christmas Special: 'Twice Upon a Time' Trailer Breakdown|last= McEwan|first= Cameron K|date= 24 July 2017|website= doctorwho.tv|publisher= BBC|accessdate= 25 July 2017}}</ref> and [[Mark Gatiss]], also writer of nine episodes between 2005 and 2017, marking his fourth acting appearance in the series, playing a character credited as The Captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-23/bill-returns-and-the-doctors-unite-in-new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures |title=Bill returns and the Doctors unite in new Doctor Who Christmas special pictures |date=24 July 2017 |accessdate=24 July 2017 |website=RadioTimes}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristmasTrailer\" /> In an interview following the episode's broadcast, Gatiss said he cried at the thought of playing the Brigadier's grandfather when he finished reading the script.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caron|first1=Nathalie|title=Mark Gatiss' Doctor Who role in Christmas special was a classic Easter egg|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/mark-gatiss-doctor-who-role-in-christmas-special-was-a-classic-easter-egg|website=Syfy Wire|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> However, the Haisman Literary Estate asserted their control of the backstory of the Brigadier, stating that Archibald was actually the Brigadier's great-uncle who appeared in ''Night of the Intelligence''.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=FrankhamAllen |number=945593164190056449 |title=It's a complicated issue, for various legal reasons, but the official stance of Haisman/Lincoln is that he's the brother of the Brig's grandfather. And as owners of the LS copyright (and derivative works), they reserve the right to make that decision.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017-12-26|language=en|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Lethbridge-Stewart : Night of the Intelligence.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017|publisher=Candy Jar Books|isbn=9780995743632|location=[S.l.]|oclc=987359707}}</ref> They later compromised in ''What's Past is Prologue'' by implying that Archibald may secretly be the biological father of the Brigadier's father, thereby allowing for either interpretation.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=946802391256576001|title=Indeed. After the last few days, I suggested a new compromise to the Haisman Estate and they agreed to it. So, currently, it's just an implication. Now fans can accept whichever, and both could well be right.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017-12-29|user=FrankhamAllen|language=en|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=What's Past is Prologue|last=McIntee|first=David A|publisher=Candy Jar Books|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIt was later confirmed that Ben Jackson, a companion of the First and [[Second Doctor]]s, who served alongside Polly, would also feature in the episode and that he would be played by the former [[Hollyoaks]] cast member Jared Garfield.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-08-24/hollyoaks-star-jared-garfield-to-play-classic-doctor-who-companion-in-christmas-special/|title= Hollyoaks star Jared Garfield to play classic Doctor Who companion in Christmas special|last= Fullerton|first= Huw|date= 24 August 2017|website= radiotimes.com|publisher= [[Radio Times]]|accessdate= 25 August 2017}}</ref> Hartnell, [[Anneke Wills]] and [[Michael Craze]] appeared as the First Doctor, Polly and Ben respectively through archive footage,<ref name=\"Radio Times\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-03/doctor-who-steven-moffat-interview-christmas-special-peter-capaldi-david-bradley-carey-mulligan/|title=Steven Moffat unveils his final Doctor Who episode \u2013 and reveals why Carey Mulligan said no to the Tardis|last=Mulkern|first=Patrick|date=3 December 2017|website=radiotimes.com|publisher=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=5 December 2017|quote=in this Christmas special when it starts we have Hartnell and the original companions}}</ref> as also did [[Patrick Troughton]] as the freshly regenerated [[Second Doctor]]. [[Nikki Amuka-Bird]] voices the \"Glass Woman\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/twice-upon-time-new-image-and-synopsis.html |title=Twice Upon A Time \u2013 New Image and Synopsis |date=28 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017|last=Marcus|work=Doctor Who News}}</ref>\n\nAs with the last change of showrunners, Chibnall wrote the final moments of the episode, so as to allow him to write Whittaker's first lines on the show. This happened in the 2010 special \"[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]\", when Moffat took over for [[Russell T Davies|Russell T. Davies]] in the final moments of the episode, writing [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]'s first words as the [[Eleventh Doctor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a824198/doctor-who-steven-moffat-confirms-that-chris-chibnall-will-write-the-new-doctors-first-words/|title=Doctor Who: Steven Moffat confirms that Chris Chibnall will write the new Doctor's first words|date=23 March 2017|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan}}</ref>\n\nThe episode includes a cameo appearance of [[Jenna Coleman]] as [[Clara Oswald]], as the Doctor's memories of Clara, lost during \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\", are restored. The scene was the last to be filmed for the episode and while Coleman was willing to come back to film, timing between the filming of this special and her work in ''[[Victoria (UK TV series)|Victoria]]'' was difficult to arrange. Moffat said \"How many times have I killed that girl off and she was right there in my last shot! It's absolutely extraordinary. The unkillable Coleman!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a846042/jenna-coleman-clara-doctor-who-christmas-twice-upon-a-time/|title=Doctor Who Christmas cameo was \"difficult to arrange\"|date=25 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nThe episode was written by [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by [[Rachel Talalay]],<ref name=\"TalalayChristmas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/05/rachel-talalay-directing-christmas_28.html|title=Rachel Talalay Directing Christmas Episode|work=Doctor Who News|last=Marcus|date=28 May 2017|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref> who wrote and directed the two-part finale of the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]], \"[[World Enough and Time (Doctor Who)|World Enough and Time]]\" / \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/adff0629-5ce5-4a0e-b81a-69693d489745|title=Original Mondasian Cybermen return to Doctor Who!|date=6 March 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/Steven-Moffat-Final-Doctor-Who-Episode-Air-142547.html|title=When Steven Moffat's Final Doctor Who Episode Will Air|first=Jessica|last=Rawden|work=Cinema Blend|date=3 June 2016|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, Moffat announced that he would step down as the programme's showrunner after the tenth series, to be replaced by [[Chris Chibnall]] beginning with the eleventh series in 2018, but a 2017 Christmas special was not mentioned in the plans at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-01-22/doctor-who-showrunner-steven-moffat-quits-to-be-replaced-by-broadchurch-creator-chris-chibnall|title=Steven Moffat quits Doctor Who to be replaced by Chris Chibnall in 2018|author=Ben Dowell|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>  The change in showrunners almost caused the annual episode to be cancelled, as Moffat planned to leave after the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]] finale and Chibnall did not want to begin his run with a Christmas special.  When he learned of Chibnall's plans, Moffat elected to stay long enough to produce one final episode, as he was concerned that the show would lose the coveted 25 December slot in the future if it missed a year.  As a result, he had to rewrite his plans for the tenth series finale to allow Capaldi to appear in one more episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a834617/doctor-who-christmas-special-almost-scrapped/ |title=Steven Moffat reveals how Doctor Who's Christmas specials almost disappeared forever |last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |date=2 August 2017 |website=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=2 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nNear the end of the special, the two Doctors part company and return to their respective TARDISes to undergo regeneration. The First Doctor's regeneration is shown, using original footage from \"The Tenth Planet\". Although the last episode of the 1966 story is one of the [[Doctor Who missing episodes|missing episodes of ''Doctor Who'']], the regeneration sequence was preserved when it was used in a 1973 edition of the children's magazine programme ''[[Blue Peter]]''.<ref name=\"denofgeek\" /><ref name=\"bbc-factfile\">{{cite web|title=Twice Upon a Time, Doctor Who \u2013 Twice Upon a Time: The Fact File \u2013 BBC One|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KWlW7Fd4q8fNmBy2JBJ3rG/twice-upon-a-time-the-fact-file|website=BBC|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226195040/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KWlW7Fd4q8fNmBy2JBJ3rG/twice-upon-a-time-the-fact-file|archivedate=26 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe final scene of \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\" involving [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] was filmed as part of the filming of \"Twice Upon a Time\" in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ac7pl1lI8FU|title=Steven Moffat & Rachel Talalay \u2013 The Aftershow \u2013 Doctor Who: The Fan Show|date=1 July 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> Production for \"Twice Upon a Time\" started on 12 June 2017, and concluded on 10 July 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=29 June 2017|title=Countdown to the Thirteenth Doctor|magazine=[[Doctor Who Magazine]]|issue=514|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/doctor-who/doctor-who-news/peter-capaldi-lifts-off-new-companion-bill-463766/|title=Doctor Who's Peter Capaldi lifts off with new companion Bill: 'Their adventures spin out of control'|date=11 April 2017|first=Nick|last=Cannon|work=[[What's on TV]]|accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-11/peter-capaldi-says-goodbye-to-fans-on-his-final-day-of-doctor-who-filming|title=Peter Capaldi says goodbye to fans on his final day of Doctor Who filming|date=11 July 2017 |first=Ben |last=Allen |work=Radio Times |accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> However, the final scene of the episode, in which Whittaker makes her debut as the Doctor, was not filmed until 19 July.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Kibble-White|first= Graham|date= August 2017|title= The XIII Chromosome|magazine= [[Doctor Who Magazine]]|location= [[Tunbridge Wells]], [[Kent]], [[United Kingdom]]|publisher= [[Panini Comics]]|edition= October 2017|issue= 516|page= 15}}</ref> The episode had been reportedly titled \"The Doctors\", before it was announced at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that it would officially be titled \"Twice Upon a Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/07/doctor-who-at-san-diego-comic-con.html|title=Doctor Who at San Diego Comic-Con|work=Doctor Who News|last=Marcus|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristmasTrailer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-23/the-2017-doctor-who-christmas-special-will-be-called|title=The 2017 Doctor Who Christmas special will be called...|work=Radio Times|date=23 July 2017|accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcast and reception ==\nThe episode was watched by 5.70 million viewers overnight, making it the fifth most watched programme of the day across all channels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/christmas-day-2017-ratings-top-10-86691.htm|title=Christmas Day 2017 Ratings Top 10 {{!}} Doctor Who TV|last=DWTV|date=2017-12-26|work=Doctor Who TV|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> The episode received 7.92 million views overall, and it received an [[Appreciation Index]] of 81.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Marcus|title=Twice Upon A Time: Official Rating|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2018/01/twice-upon-time-official-rating.html |website=Doctor Who News|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=3 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Marcus |title=Twice Upon a Time \u2013 Audience Appreciation:81 |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/12/twice-upon-time-ai81.html |website=Doctor Who News |accessdate=3 January 2018 |date=3 January 2018}}</ref> In the United States \"Twice Upon a Time\" was watched by 2.2 million viewers on [[BBC America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcwpressroom.com/bbca/press/farewell-twelfth-doctor-bbc-america-brings-record-setting-viewership-social-engagement-christmas-day/|title=Farewell to Twelfth Doctor on BBC AMERICA Brings Record-Setting Viewership and Social Engagement on Christmas Day|work=BBCW Press Room|date=4 January 2018|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cinemas ===\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" was released in cinemas in multiple countries, including Brazil on 25 December, Australia and Denmark on 26 December, and the United States and Canada on 27\u201328 December. The cinema release includes two bonus features: a behind-the-scenes view of the episode, and a special celebrating the tenure of Peter Capaldi as the Doctor and Steven Moffat as showrunner and lead writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/cinema-xmas-anz-141117070008.html|title=Australian cinema outing for Twice Upon a Time|work=Doctor Who News|last=Foster|first=Chuck|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/xmas-cinema-canada-271117190008.html|title=Twice Upon a Time to show in Canadian Cinemas|work=Doctor Who News|last=Foster|first=Chuck|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 87%<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor_who/27369|title=Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (2017 Christmas Special)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 7.28<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A-<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite web|last1=Siede|first1=Caroline|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=A poignant Doctor Who Christmas special says goodbye 12, hello 13, hello love|url=https://www.avclub.com/a-poignant-doctor-who-christmas-special-says-goodbye-12-1821573808|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = A<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/recap/doctor-who-season-10-episode-christmas-special/|title=''Doctor Who'' recap: 'Twice Upon a Time'|first=Dana|last=Schwartz|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 25, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[IndieWire]]\n| rev5Score = C+<ref name=\"IndieWire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-peter-capaldi-regeneration-spoilers-jodie-whittaker-1201910947/|title='Doctor Who' Review: Peter Capaldi Takes Too Long to Say Goodbye In Emotional Christmas Special|first=Kaite|last=Welsh|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=December 25, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[IGN]]\n| rev6Score = 9.5<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/27/doctor-who-twice-upon-a-time-review?abthid=5a42f8f85b73bccc04000008|title=Doctor Who: \"Twice Upon a Time\" Review|first=Collura|last=Scott|work=[[IGN]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NYM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/12/doctor-who-christmas-special-recap-twice-upon-a-time.html|title=''Doctor Who'' Christmas Special Recap: Postscript|first=Ross|last=Ruediger|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Radio Times]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RadioTimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-26/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-twice-upon-a-time-offers-a-warm-embracing-hug-of-nostalgia-but-is-less-than-gripping/|title=''Doctor Who'' Christmas special review: Twice upon a Time offers a warm embracing hug of nostalgia but is less than gripping|first=Patrick|last=Mulkern|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/doctor-twice-upon-time-review-cue-jodie-whittaker-raft-self/|title=Doctor Who, Twice Upon a Time, review: cue Jodie Whittaker, but only after a raft of self-indulgence|last=Hogan|first=Michael|date=2017-12-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Daily Mirror]]''\n| rev10Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"DM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-reviews/doctor-who-twice-upon-time-11750282|title=Doctor Who Series 10 Episode 13 Twice Upon A Time review: A very special Christmas adventure that rounds off Capaldi's Doctor perfectly|first=Daniel|last=Jackson|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=25 December 2017|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n| rev11 = ''[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]''\n| rev11Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/doctor-christmas-special-2017-twice-upon-time|title=DOCTOR WHO Christmas Special 2017 'Twice Upon a Time'|first=J.R.|last=Southall|website=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]|date=28 December 2017|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n| rev12 = The Tracking Board\n| rev12Score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/doctor-who-review-twice-upon-a-time/|title=DOCTOR WHO Review: \"Twice Upon a Time\"|first=Cailin|last=Coane|website=The Tracking Board|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" received generally positive reviews, who praised the script and the cast's performances (especially Capaldi, Bradley and Mackie).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/12/twice-upon-time-press-reaction.html|title=Doctor Who News \u2013 Twice Upon A Time \u2013 Press Reaction|last=newsintimeandspace.net|website=m.doctorwhonews.net|language=en|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> Michael Hogan while writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', criticised Moffat's writing and Rusty's cameo. Hogan notes that viewers \"would have been left scratching their heads in bafflement. It was self-indulgent, overcomplicated and, most unforgivably, frequently boring.\"<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /><ref name=\"RadioTimes\" /><ref name=\"EW\" /><ref name=\"AVClub\" /> It currently holds a score of 87% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average score of 7.28. The site's consensus reads \"''Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time'' pays gratifying homage to the outgoing doctor while marking a thoughtful, warm and funny passing of the torch to a new era in the franchise.\"<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n\nThe episode is a finalist in the category of [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form]] for the 2018 [[Hugo Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2018/03/2018-1943-hugo-award-finalists-announced/|title=2018/1943 Hugo Award Finalists Announced|author=|date=1 April 2018|website=thehugoawards.org}}</ref> It was also nominated for [[Saturn Award for Best Television Presentation]].<ref name=\"Nominations\">{{cite web| first1=Dave | last1=McNary | date=March 15, 2018| title='Black Panther,' 'Walking Dead' Rule Saturn Awards Nominations| website=Variety | publisher=Variety Media, LLC.| url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/| access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/saturn-awards-winners-black-panther-blade-runner-2049-shape-of-water-get-out-1202418606/ |title='Black Panther' Tops 44th Saturn Awards With Five; 'Blade Runner 2049' , 'Shape Of Water', 'Get Out' Also Score |last=Hammond |first=Pete |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 27, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628130417/https://deadline.com/2018/06/saturn-awards-winners-black-panther-blade-runner-2049-shape-of-water-get-out-1202418606/ |archivedate=June 28, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPatrick Mulkern of ''[[Radio Times]]'', despite his praise of the episode, said that the First Doctor was \"made to seem more old-fashioned than he was\".<ref name=\"RadioTimes\" /> ''[[Den of Geek]]'' reported that this was a controversial aspect of the episode even in the pre-publicity: \"the casual sexism of the first Doctor weaved unsubtly throughout this story and played for laughs.\"<ref name=\"denofgeek\" /> Moffat said that Hartnell's Doctor was \"not progressive. Without being too outrageous I think we have re-created that version of Hartnell's Doctor, with all the 1960s political incorrectness in place. At the same time the original Doctor has a lot of fun at the expense of the modern one's sonic glasses and electric guitar. There's something funny about the 12th Doctor realising that he came from this politically incorrect, funny old man. This is who he was.\"<ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-03/doctor-who-steven-moffat-interview-christmas-special-peter-capaldi-david-bradley-carey-mulligan/</ref>\n\n== Commercial releases ==\n=== Home media ===\nThe episode was released on DVD and Blu-ray in Region 2 on 22 January 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0789MZDP1/|title=Doctor Who Christmas Special 2017 \u2013 Twice Upon A Time|work=Amazon|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> in Region 4 on 7 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ezydvd.com.au/DVD/Doctor-Who-Twice-Upon-a-Time/dp/6213681 |title= Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (DVD) |work=EzyDVD |accessdate= 17 December 2017}}</ref> and in Region 1 on 13 February 2018.<ref name=\"Region1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Doctor-Who-Special-Christmas-2017/dp/B0748YHVXT/ref=tmm_dvd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1514101752&sr=8-1-spons |title=Doctor Who Christmas special set for February DVD and Blu-ray release |work=Amazon |accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" is also the first ''Doctor Who'' episode to be released on the [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] format. It was released in Region A on 25 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/BBC/Disc_Announcements/4K/doctor-who-twice-upon-a-time-headed-for-4k-ultra-hd-bluray/42068|title='Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time' Headed for 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray|work=High-Def Digest|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== In print ===\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Twice Upon a Time\n|image =\n|caption =\n|author = [[Paul Cornell]]\n|cover_artist = Anthony Dry\n|series = ''[[Doctor Who]]'' book:<br />[[List of Doctor Who novelisations|Target novelisations]]\n|release_number = \n|release_date = 5 April 2018\n|publisher = [[BBC Books]]\n|pages = 224\n|isbn = 978-1785943300\n|italic title = no\n}}\nA [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|novelisation]] of the story, written by [[Paul Cornell]], was released in paperback by [[BBC Books]] on 5 April 2018. Also on the same day, a digital edition was released, both as part of the ''Target Collection''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-11-15/doctor-who-books-steven-moffat-russell-t-davies/|title=Steven Moffat and Russell T Davies are writing special Doctor Who novels|publisher=[[Radio Times]] |date=15 November 2017 |accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (Target Collection)|work=amazon.co.uk|id={{ASIN|1785943308|country=uk}}}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christmas truce]] - Historic military truce, held in December 1914, between opposing side during Christmas.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n* {{BBCDWnew|year=2017|id=b09kkt1m|title=Twice Upon a Time}}\n* {{TardisIndexFile|Twice Upon a Time (TV story)|\"Twice Upon a Time\"}}\n* {{IMDb episode|id=6968542|title=Twice Upon a Time}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N10}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n{{Doctor Who Christmas and New Year's specials}}\n{{Regeneration stories}}\n{{Multi-Doctor stories}}\n{{Dalek stories}}\n\n[[Category:2017 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas television episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas truce]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who Christmas specials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who multi-Doctor stories]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who serials novelised by Paul Cornell]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1914]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1986]]\n[[Category:First Doctor serials]]\n[[Category:Novels by Paul Cornell]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Thirteenth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Twice Upon a Time (''Doctor Who'')}}\n{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 276\n| serial_name        = Twice Upon a Time\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| doctors            =\n* [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n* [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] ([[First Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Pearl Mackie]] ([[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]])\n| guests             = \n* [[Mark Gatiss]] \u2013 The Captain\n* [[Jenna Coleman]] \u2013 [[Clara Oswald|Clara]]\n* [[Matt Lucas]] \u2013 [[Nardole]]\n* [[Nikki Amuka-Bird]] \u2013 Helen Clay\n* [[Toby Whithouse]] \u2013 German Soldier\n* [[Lily Travers]] \u2013 [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]]\n* Jared Garfield \u2013 [[Ben Jackson (Doctor Who)|Ben Jackson]]\n* [[Nicholas Briggs]] \u2013 Voice of the [[Daleks]]\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] \u2013 [[Thirteenth Doctor|The Doctor]]\n| director           = [[Rachel Talalay]]\n| writer             = [[Steven Moffat]]\n| producer           = [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]]\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat<br>Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| length             = 60 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2017|12|25|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\"\n| following          = \"[[The Woman Who Fell to Earth]]\"\n}}\n\n\"'''Twice Upon a Time'''\" is an episode of the British [[Science fiction on television|science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', written by [[Steven Moffat]], directed by [[Rachel Talalay]], and was broadcast as the thirteenth [[List of Doctor Who Christmas specials|Christmas special]] on 25 December 2017 on [[BBC One]]. It features the final regular appearance of [[Peter Capaldi]] as the [[Twelfth Doctor]], the first official appearance of [[Jodie Whittaker]] as the [[Thirteenth Doctor]], and guest-stars [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] as the [[First Doctor]], having previously portrayed original First Doctor actor [[William Hartnell]] in the 2013 docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''. [[Pearl Mackie]] guest stars as the Twelfth Doctor's former companion [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]], while his other companions make guest appearances \u2013\n[[Jenna Coleman]] as [[Clara Oswald]] and [[Matt Lucas]] as [[Nardole]].\n\nThis episode is a continuation of events after \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", addressing the cliffhanger that it ended on, and takes place during the final story of the [[First Doctor]]; footage from the 1966 serial ''[[The Tenth Planet]]'', is used in the special. \"Twice Upon a Time\" is Capaldi's fourth and final Christmas special as the Twelfth Doctor, and the last ''Doctor Who'' story to be written and produced by Moffat, who had served as the show's executive producer and chief writer since taking over from [[Russell T Davies]] in 2010. After the special's broadcast, Moffat was succeeded as executive producer and showrunner by [[Chris Chibnall]]. It is also the last episode to have music composed by [[Murray Gold]], who had composed music for Doctor Who since the series' revival in 2005. From [[Doctor Who (series 11)|series 11]], music was composed by [[Segun Akinola]].\n\nThe special has received generally positive reviews from critics, with some criticism has been directed towards the episode's representation of the First Doctor.\n\n==Plot==\n=== Synopsis ===\nWandering back to his [[TARDIS]] through the South Pole in 1986 after leaving his companions behind, the [[First Doctor]] refuses to [[Regeneration (Doctor Who)|regenerate]]. He encounters the [[Twelfth Doctor]] outside his own TARDIS in a similar state of mind. The pair are soon approached by a confused and injured [[World War I|First World War]] British captain, displaced from December 1914 while in a gun-point stalemate with a German soldier. All three are then forcibly taken into a large spaceship. Inside, they meet with [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill]]; the Twelfth Doctor, however, doubts she is the real Bill. Upon encountering the ship's glass-like [[Holography|holographic]] pilot, they are offered freedom in exchange for allowing the ship to return the Captain to the moment of his death. Refusing to allow the Captain to die, they escape and take the First Doctor's TARDIS to the planet Villengard in the far future.\n\nAlone, the Twelfth Doctor meets with the rogue Dalek [[Into the Dalek|Rusty]], who has taken refuge from other Daleks hunting it. Given access to the Dalek Hivemind, the Doctor learns that the pilot and its ship, known as ''Testimony'', were created on New Earth, designed to extract people from their timelines at the moment of their death, and archive their memories into glass avatars. \"Bill\" is one such avatar, created from her memories. Seeing no evil to fight, the Doctors agree to return the Captain to his timeline. Upon arrival, the Captain asks the Doctors to keep an eye on his family, introducing himself as Archibald Hamish Lethbridge-Stewart, implying that he is the ancestor of the Doctor's frequent ally and lifelong friend the [[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart|Brigadier]].  As time resumes, the Doctors watch as soldiers on both sides begin singing \"[[Silent Night]]\". The Twelfth Doctor explains to the First that he deliberately shifted the Captain's timeline to the start of the [[Christmas truce]], to ensure his life would be spared.\n\nWith the Captain saved, the First Doctor informs the Twelfth that he is prepared to regenerate and says his goodbyes before returning to his TARDIS. Now alone with Bill's avatar, the Twelfth Doctor adamantly contends she is not really Bill, but she argues that memories are what define a person. Bill's avatar restores the Doctor's memories of [[Clara Oswald]] before they are joined by [[Nardole]]'s avatar. The Doctor, however, refuses to give the avatars testimony of his life. They respect his wish to be alone and leave after he embraces them both. The Doctor then returns to the TARDIS and decides it's now time to regenerate, but not before relaying advice to his next incarnation.\n\nAfter the newly regenerated [[Thirteenth Doctor]] examines her reflection, the TARDIS suffers multiple system failures due to damage caused by the delayed regeneration. Falling out of the tumbling ship, the Doctor watches in horror as the time rotor and the console room explode, and the TARDIS dematerialises while she plummets towards the Earth below.\n\n=== Continuity ===\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" takes place towards the end of the First Doctor's final serial, ''[[The Tenth Planet]]'' (first broadcast in October 1966), some of which is shown at the start of the special. During the last episode's final moments, the Doctor leaves his companions [[Ben Jackson (Doctor Who)|Ben]] and [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]] and returns to the TARDIS; they find him collapsed in the console room, where he undergoes his first regeneration. [[Derek Martinus]], the episode's director, reportedly cut a line from the original script which suggested that the Doctor was refusing to give in to the regeneration process. Steven Moffat's 2017 story creates an extended narrative around that part of the story, in which the First Doctor delays his regeneration and encounters his future self \u2014 the Twelfth Doctor \u2014 in the snowy wasteland.<ref name=\"denofgeek\">{{cite web|last1=Dillon-Trenchard|first1=Peter|title=Doctor Who: geeky spots & references in Twice Upon A Time|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/twice-upon-a-time/54180/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|website=Den of Geek|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226193632/http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/twice-upon-a-time/54180/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|archivedate=26 December 2017|language=en|date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-martin\">{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Daniel|title=Doctor Who Christmas special 2017: Twice Upon a Time|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-2017-twice-upon-a-time|website=The Guardian|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226194106/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-2017-twlewice-upon-a-time|archivedate=26 December 2017|date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Testimony shows the First Doctor images of his future incarnations, clips from both the classic series and the revival are used, including the [[Third Doctor]] from ''[[Invasion of the Dinosaurs]]'' (1974); the [[Fifth Doctor]] from ''[[Arc of Infinity]]'' (1983); the [[Seventh Doctor]] from ''[[The Happiness Patrol]]'' (1988); the [[Eighth Doctor]] from \"[[The Night of the Doctor]]\" (2013); the [[Ninth Doctor]] from \"[[The Parting of the Ways]]\" (2005); and the [[Tenth Doctor]] from \"[[The Waters of Mars]]\" (2009).<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-geeky-spots-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nTestimony also lists several of the Doctor's future titles: \"The Shadow of the [[Valeyard]]\" (from ''[[The Trial of a Time Lord]]'', said to be a distillation of the Doctor's darker side), \"the Oncoming Storm\" (\"The Parting of the Ways\"), \"the Imp of the Pandorica\" (a reference to the [[Eleventh Doctor]] story \"[[The Pandorica Opens]]\"), \"the Beast of Trenzalore\" (\"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\"), \"the Butcher of Skull Moon\" and \"the Doctor of War\" (\"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\"). \"The Destroyer of Skaro\" refers to the destruction of the planet in ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (1988), although [[Skaro]] was later restored and rebuilt; as explained in \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012) and shown in \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\" (2015).<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/>\n\nThe Weapons Factories of Villengard were originally mentioned in \"[[The Doctor Dances]]\" ([[Steven Moffat]]'s first ''Doctor Who'' story), where the Ninth Doctor implied that he was responsible for their destruction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-25/doctor-who-christmas-special-set-visit/|title=19 things we learned from the set of the Doctor Who Christmas special|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-06/theres-a-subtle-callback-to-steven-moffats-very-first-doctor-who-story-in-the-christmas-special/|title=There's a subtle callback to Steven Moffat's very first Doctor Who story in the Christmas special|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHelen Clay, who would become Testimony's glass pilot, was from New Earth and lectured at \"New Earth University,\" a reference to the Tenth Doctor stories [[New Earth (Doctor Who)|New Earth]] and [[Gridlock (Doctor Who)|Gridlock]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trenchard |first1=Pete |title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-easter-eggs-and-references-in-twice-upon-a-time |website=denofgeek.com |accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Outside references ===\nThe Doctor addresses his original incarnation as \"[[Mary Berry]]\", \"[[Lance Corporal Jones|Corporal Jones]]\", and \"Mr Pastry\".<ref name=\"denofgeek.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/doctor-who/269864/doctor-who-easter-eggs-and-references-in-twice-upon-a-time|title=Doctor Who: Easter Eggs and References in Twice Upon a Time|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> Mr Pastry was a comedic variety stage act and children's show character played by actor [[Richard Hearne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/changingwho/10303.shtml?page=9|title=BBC \u2013 Archive \u2013 The Changing Face of Doctor Who \u2013 Nearly Who|website=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> who was once considered for the role of the [[Fourth Doctor]]. Hearne, however, wanted to play the Doctor as a version of Mr. Pastry, so he was passed over in favour of [[Tom Baker]].<ref name=\"denofgeek.com1\"/>\n\nThe Doctor paraphrases philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]] when he advises his future self that \"hate is always foolish and love is always wise\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/dec/25/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-time-gentlemen-now-its-jodies-turn|title=Doctor Who Christmas special review \u2013 time, gentlemen. Now it's Jodie's turn|last=Wollaston|first=Sam|date=2017-12-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n=== Cast notes ===\n[[Peter Capaldi]] reprised his role as the [[Twelfth Doctor]]. On 30 January 2017, he confirmed that the tenth series would be his last, and that he was set to leave after the 2017 Christmas special.<ref name=\"CapaldiLeaving\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/43787cd6-f1de-4264-a509-d387d9a89c4b|title=Peter Capaldi announces he will stand down as Doctor Who at the end of the year|work=[[BBC]]|date=30 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> The episode also sees the introduction of [[Jodie Whittaker]] as the [[Thirteenth Doctor]], whose casting was announced on 16 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40608669|title=Doctor Who: New actor to be revealed after Wimbledon|work=[[BBC]]|date=14 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ThirteenthDoctorCasting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/16/doctor-jodie-whittaker-replace-peter-capaldi-time-lord-regeneration/ |title=Doctor Who: Jodie Whittaker is to replace Peter Capaldi in the Time Lord regeneration game |work=The Telegraph |date=16 July 2017 |accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who).jpg|thumb|250px|right|David Bradley's performance as the First Doctor was praised by critics.]]\nDavid Bradley appears in the episode as the First Doctor, having previously portrayed [[William Hartnell]] in the docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/4v2JXlkFdw3zvl6KF0fhgzX/the-doctor-falls-the-fact-file|title=Series 10, Doctor Who \u2013 The Doctor Falls: The Fact File \u2013 BBC One|website=BBC|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/01/first-look-pictures-first-twelfth-doctors-together-doctor-christmas/ |title=First look pictures of the First and Twelfth Doctors together in the Doctor Who Christmas special |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-02/new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures-tease-history-making-reunion-for-peter-capaldis-doctor |title=New Doctor Who Christmas special pictures tease history-making reunion for Peter Capaldi's Doctor |first=James |last=Gill |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref> This makes him the third actor to play the role in the television programme, after William Hartnell and [[Richard Hurndall]] (in 1983's ''[[The Five Doctors]]'') since the premiere of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jul/01/doctor-who-recap-series-36-finale-the-doctor-falls |title=Doctor Who recap: series 36 finale \u2013 The Doctor Falls |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Guardian}}</ref> Bradley previously played Solomon in the 2012 episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\".\n\nThe first trailer for the episode was shown during the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], revealing the return of [[Polly (Doctor Who)|Polly]], a companion from the end of [[William Hartnell]]'s tenure as the [[First Doctor]], portrayed by [[Lily Travers]],<ref name=\"Region1\" /> and [[Pearl Mackie]] as [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]]. Also confirmed were appearances by [[Toby Whithouse]], writer of seven episodes between 2006 and 2017,<ref name =\"breakdown\">{{cite web |url= http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/doctor-who-2017-christmas-special-twice-upon-a-time-trailer-breakdown |title= Doctor Who 2017 Christmas Special: 'Twice Upon a Time' Trailer Breakdown|last= McEwan|first= Cameron K|date= 24 July 2017|website= doctorwho.tv|publisher= BBC|accessdate= 25 July 2017}}</ref> and [[Mark Gatiss]], also writer of nine episodes between 2005 and 2017, marking his fourth acting appearance in the series, playing a character credited as The Captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-23/bill-returns-and-the-doctors-unite-in-new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures |title=Bill returns and the Doctors unite in new Doctor Who Christmas special pictures |date=24 July 2017 |accessdate=24 July 2017 |website=RadioTimes}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristmasTrailer\" /> In an interview following the episode's broadcast, Gatiss said he cried at the thought of playing the Brigadier's grandfather when he finished reading the script.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caron|first1=Nathalie|title=Mark Gatiss' Doctor Who role in Christmas special was a classic Easter egg|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/mark-gatiss-doctor-who-role-in-christmas-special-was-a-classic-easter-egg|website=Syfy Wire|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> However, the Haisman Literary Estate asserted their control of the backstory of the Brigadier, stating that Archibald was actually the Brigadier's great-uncle who appeared in ''Night of the Intelligence''.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=FrankhamAllen |number=945593164190056449 |title=It's a complicated issue, for various legal reasons, but the official stance of Haisman/Lincoln is that he's the brother of the Brig's grandfather. And as owners of the LS copyright (and derivative works), they reserve the right to make that decision.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017-12-26|language=en|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Lethbridge-Stewart : Night of the Intelligence.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017|publisher=Candy Jar Books|isbn=9780995743632|location=[S.l.]|oclc=987359707}}</ref> They later compromised in ''What's Past is Prologue'' by implying that Archibald may secretly be the biological father of the Brigadier's father, thereby allowing for either interpretation.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=946802391256576001|title=Indeed. After the last few days, I suggested a new compromise to the Haisman Estate and they agreed to it. So, currently, it's just an implication. Now fans can accept whichever, and both could well be right.|last=Frankham-Allen|first=Andy|date=2017-12-29|user=FrankhamAllen|language=en|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=What's Past is Prologue|last=McIntee|first=David A|publisher=Candy Jar Books|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIt was later confirmed that Ben Jackson, a companion of the First and [[Second Doctor]]s, who served alongside Polly, would also feature in the episode and that he would be played by the former [[Hollyoaks]] cast member Jared Garfield.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-08-24/hollyoaks-star-jared-garfield-to-play-classic-doctor-who-companion-in-christmas-special/|title= Hollyoaks star Jared Garfield to play classic Doctor Who companion in Christmas special|last= Fullerton|first= Huw|date= 24 August 2017|website= radiotimes.com|publisher= [[Radio Times]]|accessdate= 25 August 2017}}</ref> Hartnell, [[Anneke Wills]] and [[Michael Craze]] appeared as the First Doctor, Polly and Ben respectively through archive footage,<ref name=\"Radio Times\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-03/doctor-who-steven-moffat-interview-christmas-special-peter-capaldi-david-bradley-carey-mulligan/|title=Steven Moffat unveils his final Doctor Who episode \u2013 and reveals why Carey Mulligan said no to the Tardis|last=Mulkern|first=Patrick|date=3 December 2017|website=radiotimes.com|publisher=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=5 December 2017|quote=in this Christmas special when it starts we have Hartnell and the original companions}}</ref> as also did [[Patrick Troughton]] as the freshly regenerated [[Second Doctor]]. [[Nikki Amuka-Bird]] voices the \"Glass Woman\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/twice-upon-time-new-image-and-synopsis.html |title=Twice Upon A Time \u2013 New Image and Synopsis |date=28 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017|last=Marcus|work=Doctor Who News}}</ref>\n\nAs with the last change of showrunners, Chibnall wrote the final moments of the episode, so as to allow him to write Whittaker's first lines on the show. This happened in the 2010 special \"[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]\", when Moffat took over for [[Russell T Davies|Russell T. Davies]] in the final moments of the episode, writing [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]'s first words as the [[Eleventh Doctor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a824198/doctor-who-steven-moffat-confirms-that-chris-chibnall-will-write-the-new-doctors-first-words/|title=Doctor Who: Steven Moffat confirms that Chris Chibnall will write the new Doctor's first words|date=23 March 2017|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan}}</ref>\n\nThe episode includes a cameo appearance of [[Jenna Coleman]] as [[Clara Oswald]], as the Doctor's memories of Clara, lost during \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\", are restored. The scene was the last to be filmed for the episode and while Coleman was willing to come back to film, timing between the filming of this special and her work in ''[[Victoria (UK TV series)|Victoria]]'' was difficult to arrange. Moffat said \"How many times have I killed that girl off and she was right there in my last shot! It's absolutely extraordinary. The unkillable Coleman!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a846042/jenna-coleman-clara-doctor-who-christmas-twice-upon-a-time/|title=Doctor Who Christmas cameo was \"difficult to arrange\"|date=25 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nThe episode was written by [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by [[Rachel Talalay]],<ref name=\"TalalayChristmas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/05/rachel-talalay-directing-christmas_28.html|title=Rachel Talalay Directing Christmas Episode|work=Doctor Who News|last=Marcus|date=28 May 2017|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref> who wrote and directed the two-part finale of the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]], \"[[World Enough and Time (Doctor Who)|World Enough and Time]]\" / \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/adff0629-5ce5-4a0e-b81a-69693d489745|title=Original Mondasian Cybermen return to Doctor Who!|date=6 March 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/Steven-Moffat-Final-Doctor-Who-Episode-Air-142547.html|title=When Steven Moffat's Final Doctor Who Episode Will Air|first=Jessica|last=Rawden|work=Cinema Blend|date=3 June 2016|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, Moffat announced that he would step down as the programme's showrunner after the tenth series, to be replaced by [[Chris Chibnall]] beginning with the eleventh series in 2018, but a 2017 Christmas special was not mentioned in the plans at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-01-22/doctor-who-showrunner-steven-moffat-quits-to-be-replaced-by-broadchurch-creator-chris-chibnall|title=Steven Moffat quits Doctor Who to be replaced by Chris Chibnall in 2018|author=Ben Dowell|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>  The change in showrunners almost caused the annual episode to be cancelled, as Moffat planned to leave after the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]] finale and Chibnall did not want to begin his run with a Christmas special.  When he learned of Chibnall's plans, Moffat elected to stay long enough to produce one final episode, as he was concerned that the show would lose the coveted 25 December slot in the future if it missed a year.  As a result, he had to rewrite his plans for the tenth series finale to allow Capaldi to appear in one more episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/doctor-who/news/a834617/doctor-who-christmas-special-almost-scrapped/ |title=Steven Moffat reveals how Doctor Who's Christmas specials almost disappeared forever |last=Jeffery |first=Morgan |date=2 August 2017 |website=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=2 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nNear the end of the special, the two Doctors part company and return to their respective TARDISes to undergo regeneration. The First Doctor's regeneration is shown, using original footage from \"The Tenth Planet\". Although the last episode of the 1966 story is one of the [[Doctor Who missing episodes|missing episodes of ''Doctor Who'']], the regeneration sequence was preserved when it was used in a 1973 edition of the children's magazine programme ''[[Blue Peter]]''.<ref name=\"denofgeek\" /><ref name=\"bbc-factfile\">{{cite web|title=Twice Upon a Time, Doctor Who \u2013 Twice Upon a Time: The Fact File \u2013 BBC One|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KWlW7Fd4q8fNmBy2JBJ3rG/twice-upon-a-time-the-fact-file|website=BBC|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226195040/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KWlW7Fd4q8fNmBy2JBJ3rG/twice-upon-a-time-the-fact-file|archivedate=26 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe final scene of \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\" involving [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] was filmed as part of the filming of \"Twice Upon a Time\" in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ac7pl1lI8FU|title=Steven Moffat & Rachel Talalay \u2013 The Aftershow \u2013 Doctor Who: The Fan Show|date=1 July 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> Production for \"Twice Upon a Time\" started on 12 June 2017, and concluded on 10 July 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=29 June 2017|title=Countdown to the Thirteenth Doctor|magazine=[[Doctor Who Magazine]]|issue=514|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/doctor-who/doctor-who-news/peter-capaldi-lifts-off-new-companion-bill-463766/|title=Doctor Who's Peter Capaldi lifts off with new companion Bill: 'Their adventures spin out of control'|date=11 April 2017|first=Nick|last=Cannon|work=[[What's on TV]]|accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-11/peter-capaldi-says-goodbye-to-fans-on-his-final-day-of-doctor-who-filming|title=Peter Capaldi says goodbye to fans on his final day of Doctor Who filming|date=11 July 2017 |first=Ben |last=Allen |work=Radio Times |accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> However, the final scene of the episode, in which Whittaker makes her debut as the Doctor, was not filmed until 19 July.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Kibble-White|first= Graham|date= August 2017|title= The XIII Chromosome|magazine= [[Doctor Who Magazine]]|location= [[Tunbridge Wells]], [[Kent]], [[United Kingdom]]|publisher= [[Panini Comics]]|edition= October 2017|issue= 516|page= 15}}</ref> The episode had been reportedly titled \"The Doctors\", before it was announced at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that it would officially be titled \"Twice Upon a Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/07/doctor-who-at-san-diego-comic-con.html|title=Doctor Who at San Diego Comic-Con|work=Doctor Who News|last=Marcus|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristmasTrailer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-23/the-2017-doctor-who-christmas-special-will-be-called|title=The 2017 Doctor Who Christmas special will be called...|work=Radio Times|date=23 July 2017|accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcast and reception ==\nThe episode was watched by 5.70 million viewers overnight, making it the fifth most watched programme of the day across all channels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/christmas-day-2017-ratings-top-10-86691.htm|title=Christmas Day 2017 Ratings Top 10 {{!}} Doctor Who TV|last=DWTV|date=2017-12-26|work=Doctor Who TV|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> The episode received 7.92 million views overall, and it received an [[Appreciation Index]] of 81.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Marcus|title=Twice Upon A Time: Official Rating|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2018/01/twice-upon-time-official-rating.html |website=Doctor Who News|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=3 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Marcus |title=Twice Upon a Time \u2013 Audience Appreciation:81 |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/12/twice-upon-time-ai81.html |website=Doctor Who News |accessdate=3 January 2018 |date=3 January 2018}}</ref> In the United States \"Twice Upon a Time\" was watched by 2.2 million viewers on [[BBC America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcwpressroom.com/bbca/press/farewell-twelfth-doctor-bbc-america-brings-record-setting-viewership-social-engagement-christmas-day/|title=Farewell to Twelfth Doctor on BBC AMERICA Brings Record-Setting Viewership and Social Engagement on Christmas Day|work=BBCW Press Room|date=4 January 2018|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cinemas ===\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" was released in cinemas in multiple countries, including Brazil on 25 December, Australia and Denmark on 26 December, and the United States and Canada on 27\u201328 December. The cinema release includes two bonus features: a behind-the-scenes view of the episode, and a special celebrating the tenure of Peter Capaldi as the Doctor and Steven Moffat as showrunner and lead writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/cinema-xmas-anz-141117070008.html|title=Australian cinema outing for Twice Upon a Time|work=Doctor Who News|last=Foster|first=Chuck|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/11/xmas-cinema-canada-271117190008.html|title=Twice Upon a Time to show in Canadian Cinemas|work=Doctor Who News|last=Foster|first=Chuck|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 87%<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor_who/27369|title=Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (2017 Christmas Special)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 7.28<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A-<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite web|last1=Siede|first1=Caroline|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|title=A poignant Doctor Who Christmas special says goodbye 12, hello 13, hello love|url=https://www.avclub.com/a-poignant-doctor-who-christmas-special-says-goodbye-12-1821573808|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = A<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/recap/doctor-who-season-10-episode-christmas-special/|title=''Doctor Who'' recap: 'Twice Upon a Time'|first=Dana|last=Schwartz|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 25, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[IndieWire]]\n| rev5Score = C+<ref name=\"IndieWire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-peter-capaldi-regeneration-spoilers-jodie-whittaker-1201910947/|title='Doctor Who' Review: Peter Capaldi Takes Too Long to Say Goodbye In Emotional Christmas Special|first=Kaite|last=Welsh|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=December 25, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[IGN]]\n| rev6Score = 9.5<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/27/doctor-who-twice-upon-a-time-review?abthid=5a42f8f85b73bccc04000008|title=Doctor Who: \"Twice Upon a Time\" Review|first=Collura|last=Scott|work=[[IGN]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NYM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/12/doctor-who-christmas-special-recap-twice-upon-a-time.html|title=''Doctor Who'' Christmas Special Recap: Postscript|first=Ross|last=Ruediger|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Radio Times]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RadioTimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-26/doctor-who-christmas-special-review-twice-upon-a-time-offers-a-warm-embracing-hug-of-nostalgia-but-is-less-than-gripping/|title=''Doctor Who'' Christmas special review: Twice upon a Time offers a warm embracing hug of nostalgia but is less than gripping|first=Patrick|last=Mulkern|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/doctor-twice-upon-time-review-cue-jodie-whittaker-raft-self/|title=Doctor Who, Twice Upon a Time, review: cue Jodie Whittaker, but only after a raft of self-indulgence|last=Hogan|first=Michael|date=2017-12-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Daily Mirror]]''\n| rev10Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"DM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-reviews/doctor-who-twice-upon-time-11750282|title=Doctor Who Series 10 Episode 13 Twice Upon A Time review: A very special Christmas adventure that rounds off Capaldi's Doctor perfectly|first=Daniel|last=Jackson|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=25 December 2017|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n| rev11 = ''[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]''\n| rev11Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/doctor-christmas-special-2017-twice-upon-time|title=DOCTOR WHO Christmas Special 2017 'Twice Upon a Time'|first=J.R.|last=Southall|website=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]|date=28 December 2017|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n| rev12 = The Tracking Board\n| rev12Score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/doctor-who-review-twice-upon-a-time/|title=DOCTOR WHO Review: \"Twice Upon a Time\"|first=Cailin|last=Coane|website=The Tracking Board|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" received generally positive reviews, who praised the script and the cast's performances (especially Capaldi, Bradley and Mackie).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2017/12/twice-upon-time-press-reaction.html|title=Doctor Who News \u2013 Twice Upon A Time \u2013 Press Reaction|last=newsintimeandspace.net|website=m.doctorwhonews.net|language=en|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> Michael Hogan while writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', criticised Moffat's writing and Rusty's cameo. Hogan notes that viewers \"would have been left scratching their heads in bafflement. It was self-indulgent, overcomplicated and, most unforgivably, frequently boring.\"<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /><ref name=\"RadioTimes\" /><ref name=\"EW\" /><ref name=\"AVClub\" /> It currently holds a score of 87% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average score of 7.28. The site's consensus reads \"''Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time'' pays gratifying homage to the outgoing doctor while marking a thoughtful, warm and funny passing of the torch to a new era in the franchise.\"<ref name=\"Rotten Tomatoes\" />\n\nThe episode is a finalist in the category of [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation#Short Form|Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form]] for the 2018 [[Hugo Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2018/03/2018-1943-hugo-award-finalists-announced/|title=2018/1943 Hugo Award Finalists Announced|author=|date=1 April 2018|website=thehugoawards.org}}</ref> It was also nominated for [[Saturn Award for Best Television Presentation]].<ref name=\"Nominations\">{{cite web| first1=Dave | last1=McNary | date=March 15, 2018| title='Black Panther,' 'Walking Dead' Rule Saturn Awards Nominations| website=Variety | publisher=Variety Media, LLC.| url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/| access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/saturn-awards-winners-black-panther-blade-runner-2049-shape-of-water-get-out-1202418606/ |title='Black Panther' Tops 44th Saturn Awards With Five; 'Blade Runner 2049' , 'Shape Of Water', 'Get Out' Also Score |last=Hammond |first=Pete |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 27, 2018 |accessdate=June 28, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628130417/https://deadline.com/2018/06/saturn-awards-winners-black-panther-blade-runner-2049-shape-of-water-get-out-1202418606/ |archivedate=June 28, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPatrick Mulkern of ''[[Radio Times]]'', despite his praise of the episode, said that the First Doctor was \"made to seem more old-fashioned than he was\".<ref name=\"RadioTimes\" /> ''[[Den of Geek]]'' reported that this was a controversial aspect of the episode even in the pre-publicity: \"the casual sexism of the first Doctor weaved unsubtly throughout this story and played for laughs.\"<ref name=\"denofgeek\" /> Moffat said that Hartnell's Doctor was \"not progressive. Without being too outrageous I think we have re-created that version of Hartnell's Doctor, with all the 1960s political incorrectness in place. At the same time the original Doctor has a lot of fun at the expense of the modern one's sonic glasses and electric guitar. There's something funny about the 12th Doctor realising that he came from this politically incorrect, funny old man. This is who he was.\"<ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-12-03/doctor-who-steven-moffat-interview-christmas-special-peter-capaldi-david-bradley-carey-mulligan/</ref>\n\n== Commercial releases ==\n=== Home media ===\nThe episode was released on DVD and Blu-ray in Region 2 on 22 January 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0789MZDP1/|title=Doctor Who Christmas Special 2017 \u2013 Twice Upon A Time|work=Amazon|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> in Region 4 on 7 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ezydvd.com.au/DVD/Doctor-Who-Twice-Upon-a-Time/dp/6213681 |title= Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (DVD) |work=EzyDVD |accessdate= 17 December 2017}}</ref> and in Region 1 on 13 February 2018.<ref name=\"Region1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Doctor-Who-Special-Christmas-2017/dp/B0748YHVXT/ref=tmm_dvd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1514101752&sr=8-1-spons |title=Doctor Who Christmas special set for February DVD and Blu-ray release |work=Amazon |accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Twice Upon a Time\" is also the first ''Doctor Who'' episode to be released on the [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] format. It was released in Region A on 25 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/BBC/Disc_Announcements/4K/doctor-who-twice-upon-a-time-headed-for-4k-ultra-hd-bluray/42068|title='Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time' Headed for 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray|work=High-Def Digest|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== In print ===\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Twice Upon a Time\n|image =\n|caption =\n|author = [[Paul Cornell]]\n|cover_artist = Anthony Dry\n|series = ''[[Doctor Who]]'' book:<br />[[List of Doctor Who novelisations|Target novelisations]]\n|release_number = \n|release_date = 5 April 2018\n|publisher = [[BBC Books]]\n|pages = 224\n|isbn = 978-1785943300\n|italic title = no\n}}\nA [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|novelisation]] of the story, written by [[Paul Cornell]], was released in paperback by [[BBC Books]] on 5 April 2018. Also on the same day, a digital edition was released, both as part of the ''Target Collection''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2017-11-15/doctor-who-books-steven-moffat-russell-t-davies/|title=Steven Moffat and Russell T Davies are writing special Doctor Who novels|publisher=[[Radio Times]] |date=15 November 2017 |accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Doctor Who: Twice Upon a Time (Target Collection)|work=amazon.co.uk|id={{ASIN|1785943308|country=uk}}}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christmas truce]] - Historic military truce, held in December 1914, between opposing side during Christmas.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n* {{BBCDWnew|year=2017|id=b09kkt1m|title=Twice Upon a Time}}\n* {{TardisIndexFile|Twice Upon a Time (TV story)|\"Twice Upon a Time\"}}\n* {{IMDb episode|id=6968542|title=Twice Upon a Time}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N10}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n{{Doctor Who Christmas and New Year's specials}}\n{{Regeneration stories}}\n{{Multi-Doctor stories}}\n{{Dalek stories}}\n\n[[Category:2017 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas television episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas truce]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who Christmas specials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who multi-Doctor stories]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who serials novelised by Paul Cornell]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1914]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1986]]\n[[Category:First Doctor serials]]\n[[Category:Novels by Paul Cornell]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Thirteenth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about World War I]]\n", "name_user": "ArkhamBen17", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast notes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twice_Upon_a_Time_(Doctor_Who)"}
{"title_page": "Mario Kart", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{for|the first game in the series|Super Mario Kart}}\n{{Infobox VG series\n| width =\n| title = Mario Kart\n| creator = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| collapsible =\n| state = Ongoing\n| image = Mario Kart logo.png\n| caption = Logo used since Mario Kart DS\n| developer = {{ubl|[[Nintendo EAD]]|[[Intelligent Systems]] {{small|(''Super Circuit'')}}|[[Retro Studios]] {{small|(''Mario Kart 7'')}}|[[Namco]]/[[Namco Bandai Games|Namco Bandai]] {{small|(''[[Mario Kart Arcade GP|Arcade GP]]'' series)}}}}\n| publisher = Nintendo\n| genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]]|[[Nintendo 64]]|[[iQue Player]]|[[Game Boy Advance]]|[[GameCube]]|[[Nintendo DS]]|[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|[[Wii]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[Wii U]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]|[[iOS]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]}}\n| first release version = ''[[Super Mario Kart]]''\n| first release date = {{start date|1992|08|27}}\n| latest release version = ''[[Mario Kart Tour]]''\n| latest release date = {{start date|2019|09|25}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario Kart'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8|Mario K\u0101to|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[kart racing game|go-kart-style]] [[racing video game]]s developed and published by [[Nintendo]] as spin-offs from its trademark [[Super Mario]] series. The first in the series, ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'', was launched in 1992 on the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] to critical and commercial success.<ref>Crecente, Brian (2009-26-2). \"[http://kotaku.com/5160745/super-mario-kart-most-influential-video-game-in-history Super Mario Kart: Most Influential Video Game in History].\" ''Kotaku.'' Retrieved January 27, 2012.</ref>\n\nWith six ''Mario Kart'' games released on home consoles, three on portable handheld consoles, four arcade games co-developed with [[Namco]] and one for mobile phones, the ''Mario Kart'' series includes a total of fourteen entries. The latest game in the main series, ''[[Mario Kart Tour]]'', was released on iOS and Android in September 2019. The series has sold over 100 million copies worldwide to date.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mario kart first logo.png|thumb|right|The original logo, used up until ''Mario Kart Arcade GP 2'']]\nThe first title in the ''Mario Kart'' series, ''[[Super Mario Kart]],'' was released for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] in 1992. The development of the first game was overseen by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]], the Japanese video game designer who created the original ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' as well as many other successful games for Nintendo. Darran Jones of [[Imagine Publishing|NowGamer]] suggests that the original success of ''Super Mario Kart'' was the result of including characters previously seen in ''Mario Bros.'' games, while also being a new type of racing game.<ref name=\"Now Gamer\">{{cite web|title=Super Mario Kart: The Complete History of Nintendo's Kart Racer |url=http://www.nowgamer.com/features/1148204/super_mario_kart_the_complete_history_of_nintendos_kart_racer.html |last=Jones |first=Darran |work=[[NowGamer]] |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing|Imagine Publishing Ltd.]] |date=November 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625232227/http://www.nowgamer.com/features/1148204/super_mario_kart_the_complete_history_of_nintendos_kart_racer.html |archivedate=June 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:MK8 Mario Circuit.jpg|thumb|right|Mario driving upside-down using the anti-gravity mechanic introduced in ''[[Mario Kart 8]]''.]]\nIn the ''Mario Kart'' series, players compete in [[Kart racing|go-kart races]], controlling one of a selection of characters, typically from the ''Mario'' franchise. Up to twelve characters can compete in each race; the exact number varies between games.\n\nOne of the features of the series is the use of various [[power-up]] items obtained by driving into item boxes laid out on the course. These power-ups include [[Super Mario (series)#Mushrooms|mushrooms]] to give players a speed boost, [[Koopa Troopa|Koopa]] Shells to be thrown at opponents, [[banana peel]]s and fake item boxes that can be laid on the course as hazards. The type of weapon received from an item box is influenced by the player's current position in the race.<ref name=WM>{{cite web|last=Dan|title=Mario Kart Franchise Retrospective|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/title/Mario%20Kart%20Franchise%20Retrospective/|publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]]|accessdate=February 5, 2012}}</ref> For example, players lagging far behind may receive more powerful items, such as Bullet Bills which give the player a bigger speed boost depending on the place of the player, while the leader may only receive small defensive items, such as shells or bananas. Called [[Dynamic game difficulty balancing|rubber banding]], this gameplay mechanism allows other players or computers a realistic chance to catch up to the leading player. They can also perform driving techniques during the race such as rocket starts, [[slipstream]]ing, and mini-turbos.\n\nAs the series has progressed, each new installment has introduced new gameplay elements, such as new circuits, items, modes, and playable characters.<ref name=WM/> These changes include:\n\n* ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'' introduces 4-player racing, slipstreaming<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariowiki.com/Slipstreaming|title=Slipstreaming|website=Super Mario Wiki|language=en|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref> and [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]].<ref name=WM/> This game also introduced [[Wario]] and [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]] as playable characters, as well as seven new items: the Fake Item Box, Triple Red Shell, Triple Green Shell, Triple Mushroom, Banana Bunch, Golden Mushroom, and the infamous [[blue shell]]. In addition to the three Grand Prix engine classes, Mirror mode is introduced (tracks are flipped laterally) in 100cc.\n* ''[[Mario Kart: Super Circuit]]'' introduces the ability to unlock all of the ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'' tracks, as both games use the same [[mode 7]] principle.\n* ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash]]'' features [[co-operative]] [[LAN]] play and two-player karts.<ref name=WM/> It also introduces eleven new playable characters ([[Princess Daisy]], [[Birdo]], Baby Mario, Baby Luigi, Paratroopa, [[Diddy Kong]], [[Bowser Jr.]], [[Waluigi]], [[Toadette]], [[List of Mario franchise characters#Petey Piranha|Petey Piranha]], and [[King Boo]]). The game also features special items that are specific to each character, a feature that was previously accessible only to computer-controlled drivers in the original game and re-introduced in ''Mario Kart Tour''. Finally, this game introduced unlockable characters and karts to the series. Mirror mode is bumped up to 150cc.\n* ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'' features [[dual-screen]] play and introduces [[online multiplayer]] (via [[Wi-Fi]]) & retro battle arenas. Shy Guy (exclusive to [[DS Download Play]]), Dry Bones, and [[R.O.B.]] are introduced as playable characters. ''DS'' was also the first ''Mario Kart'' game to feature retro tracks from all previous titles of the series, as well as the first entry in the series to feature mission mode. It also introduces two new items: the Blooper, which temporarily obscures the screens of players in higher places with ink and Bullet Bill, which is given to players in lower places and grants a larger speed boost depending on the position from first place.\n* ''[[Mario Kart Wii]]'' introduces motion controls, performing tricks, 12-player racing, and [[motorbikes]].<ref name=\"Mario Kart Wii Details\">{{cite web | url=http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed | title=Mario Kart Wii Detailed | publisher=1up.com | date=February 6, 2008 | accessdate=May 21, 2013 | author=Sato, Yoshi | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192825/http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed | archivedate=October 29, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Six new playable characters were introduced: Baby Peach, Baby Daisy, [[Rosalina (Mario)|Rosalina]], Funky Kong, Dry Bowser, and two outfits for [[Mii]] characters. It also introduced three new items: the [[New Super Mario Bros.|Mega Mushroom]], Thunder Cloud, and [[Mario Bros.|POW Block]], the last two of which are only seen in this game. This game also marks the final appearance for the Fake Item Box.\n* ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' features [[Stereoscopy|stereoscopic 3D graphics]], introduces [[hang gliders|hang gliding]] and [[Amphibious vehicle|submersible]] karts, as well as an alternate [[First-person (video games)|first-person]] perspective and kart customization.<ref name=\"WM\" /> Introduces Metal Mario, [[Lakitu]], Wiggler, and Honey Queen as new playable characters. It is also the first ''Mario Kart'' game after ''Mario Kart: Double Dash'' not to feature Waluigi as a playable character. This title also re-introduces collectible coins to give players a small speed boost.\n* ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' introduces 200cc mode, [[anti-gravity]] racing, [[All-terrain vehicle|ATVs]], uploading highlights to [[YouTube]] via Mario Kart TV (exclusive to the Wii U version), up to four local players in [[Grand Prix motor racing|Grand Prix]] races, [[downloadable content]], and is the first in the series to boast [[High-definition television|HD graphics]]. ''Mario Kart 8'' introduces the [[Koopalings]], Baby Rosalina, Pink Gold Peach, Tanooki Mario, Cat Peach, Villager and [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''[[Animal Crossing]]'', and [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] from ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' as new playable characters.<ref name=\"MK8 DLC\" /> The Nintendo Switch version, ''Mario Kart 8 Deluxe'', also adds the Inkling Girl and Inkling Boy from ''[[Splatoon]]'' as playable characters for the first time in the series, as well as a new battle mode, \"Renegade Roundup\", which plays similarly to a game of [[Tag (game)|tag]].\n*''[[Mario Kart Tour]]'' introduces [[Pauline (Mario)|Pauline]] to the series. Alternate outfits for certain characters are also available as rare items. This is the first ''Mario Kart'' game to be released for a non-Nintendo device and introduces [[Gacha game|gacha]] and [[loot box]] mechanics, as well as continuously-renewing character outfits and karts. Character-specific items and increased item probabilities have been re-added. The Mega Mushroom also makes its return after an eleven-year absence. The game also added Frenzy Mode, which happens when the character receives three of the same item during the race.\n===Characters===\n{{Main|Characters in the Mario Kart series}}\n''Mario Kart'' mainly features [[List of Mario franchise characters|characters from the ''Mario'' franchise]]. The ''[[Mario Kart Arcade GP]]'' series features [[Bandai Namco]] characters such as [[Pac-Man (character)|Pac-Man]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mario Kart Arcade GP |url=https://www.nintendolife.com/games/triforce/mario_kart_arcade_gp |website=Nintendo Life |accessdate=April 5, 2019|date=December 2011 }}</ref> The [[Downloadable content|DLC]] for ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' added [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] from ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'', and Villager and [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]] from ''[[Animal Crossing]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matulef |first1=Jeffrey |title=Mario Kart 8 getting Zelda and Animal Crossing DLC |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-08-26-mario-kart-8-is-getting-zelda-and-animal-crossing-dlc |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |date=August 27, 2014}}</ref> ''Mario Kart 8 Deluxe'' features 42 characters, including the Inklings from ''[[Splatoon]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bashore |first1=Nicholas |title=Here's Every New Character in 'Mario Kart 8 Deluxe' |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/30945-mario-kart-8-deluxe-all-new-characters-gold-mario-unlock |website=Inverse |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |language=en |date=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Courses===\nMany course themes recur throughout the series. Most are based on existing areas in the ''Mario'' franchise ([[Mushroom Kingdom#Bowser's Castle|Bowser's Castle]] being among the most prominent), but there are a number of courses that have not appeared elsewhere, yet still belong in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]], such as Rainbow Road, which usually takes place above a city or in space.<ref name=WM/> Each game in the series (following the original game) includes at least 16 original courses and up to 6 original battle arenas.<ref name=WM/> Each game's tracks are divided into four \"cups\", or groups in which the player has to have the highest overall placing to win and they are the Mushroom Cup, the Flower Cup, the Star Cup, and the Special Cup. Most courses can be done in three laps, except in the original game where all circuits required five laps to finish, seven in ''Mario Kart: Double Dash!!'' when racing on Baby Park, and ''Mario Kart Tour'' with only two. The first game to feature courses from previous games was ''Mario Kart: Super Circuit'', which contained all of the tracks from the original Super NES game. Starting with ''Mario Kart DS'', each entry in the series has featured 16 \"nitro\" (brand new courses introduced for said game) and 16 \"retro\" tracks (reappearing courses from previous ''Mario Kart'' games), spread across four cups each with four races. The four Retro Grand Prix cups are the Shell Cup, the Banana Cup, the Leaf Cup, and the Lightning Cup. In ''Mario Kart 8'', 16 additional tracks are available across two [[Downloadable content|downloadable]] packages, eight for each package downloaded, including seven retro courses, four original courses, and five courses based on other Nintendo franchises, including ''[[Excitebike]]'', ''[[F-Zero]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'', and ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' divided into four additional cups; the Egg Cup, the [[Triforce]] Cup, the Crossing Cup, and the Bell Cup.<ref name=\"MK8 DLC\">{{cite web|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/26/6071823/mario-kart-8-link-animal-crossing-dlc|title=Link, F-Zero and Animal Crossing are coming to Mario Kart 8 as DLC|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> ''Mario Kart Tour'' introduced courses from around the world including [[Paris]], [[Tokyo]], [[London]], [[Vancouver]], and [[New York City]].\n\n===Modes of play===\nEach installment features a variety of different modes. The following four modes recur most often in the series:\n* '''Grand Prix''' \u2013 Players compete in various \"cups,\" of four courses each (five in ''Super Mario Kart'') with [[difficulty levels]] based on the size of the engine, larger engines meaning faster speeds. Before ''Mario Kart 8'' there were four difficulties: 50[[Cubic centimeter|cc]], 100cc, 150cc, and 150cc Mirror (courses that see their circuits flipped horizontally, originally 100cc Mirror in ''Mario Kart 64''). ''Mario Kart 8'' added a fifth difficulty level: 200cc. Players earn points according to their finishing position in each race and the placement order gets carried over as the starting grid for the next race. At the end of the cup, the top three players with the most points overall will receive a [[trophy]] in bronze, silver, and gold.\n* '''[[Time trial|Time Trials]]''' \u2013 The player races alone in order to finish any course in the fastest time possible. The best time is then saved as a [[Ghost (video gaming)|ghost]], which the player can race against in later trials. Since ''Mario Kart: Double Dash'', a new function called Staff Ghosts is introduced, Staff Ghosts are members of the Nintendo development team that set staff times for players to try and beat. Upon success, players will unlock Expert Staff Ghosts, which only appeared in ''Mario Kart Wii'' and ''Mario Kart 7'', which unlock characters, vehicles, or stamps once beaten, in addition to viewing ghost data.\n* '''VS Race''' \u2013 Multiple human players race against each other on any course with customized rules such as team racing and item frequency. The mode also includes [[single-player]] VS races and CPU controlled players to compete in VS races as well since ''Mario Kart DS'' (except for ''Mario Kart 7''). ''Super Circuit'', however, features a Quick Run mode, which shares similarities with VS mode.\n* '''Battle''' \u2013 Multiple human players use in-game offensive items (shells, etc.) to battle each other in a closed arena. Each player starts with three [[balloons]] and loses a balloon with every hit sustained; the last player possessing at least one balloon wins. Different battle types were added as the series progressed, as well as single-player battles with CPU controlled players. Starting with ''Mario Kart Wii'', there is a [[Time limit (video gaming)|time limit]] for each battle. For ''Mario Kart 8'', the battles take place on race courses. ''Mario Kart 8 Deluxe'' reintroduces dedicated arenas.\n*'''Online Multiplayer''' \u2013 Players are able to compete in races and battles through online services, such as [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]], [[Nintendo Network]], and [[Nintendo Switch Online]]. Players can also share Time Trial ghosts, and participate in [[tournament]]s. In races and battles, players are matched by VR (VS Rating) and BR (Battle Rating) respectively, which is a number between 0 and 99,999 (only 9,999 in ''Mario Kart Wii''). Players gain or lose points based on their performance in a race or battle. The game attempts to match players with a similar rating.\n\n==List of ''Mario Kart'' games==\n{{VG timeline\n|range1 = 1992-\n|range1_color = #6cbe45 #218800\n| 1992 = ''[[Super Mario Kart]]''\n| 1995 = ''[[VB Mario Kart]]'' (Cancelled)\n| 1996 = ''[[Mario Kart 64]]''\n| 2001 = ''[[Mario Kart: Super Circuit]]''\n| 2003 = ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash]]''\n| 2005a = ''[[Mario Kart Arcade GP]]''\n| 2005b = ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'' \